whether her Department plans to seek professional photographic trade association (a) accreditation, (b) sanction and (c) support for proposals to encourage digital identification photographs to be used in passport applications.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","41609"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531478","Home Office","false","2016-07-11","<p>Her Majesty’s Passport Office does not hold the information in the requested format and this information cannot be provided except at disproportionate cost.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-07-11T16:23:22.997Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531478/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531478/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531478/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-01","Passports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the cost was to HM Passport Office of handling and processing rejected passport applications in each of the last three years; and on what those costs were incurred.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","41613"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531479","Home Office","false","2016-07-12","<p>HM Passport Office records indicate that during the period 1 July 2015 to 30 June 2016: 219,508 passport applications had a query raised for the photograph not being acceptable and with a further photograph requested.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-07-12T14:05:30.217Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531479/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531479/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531479/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-01","Passports: Photographs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many passport applications were rejected by HM Passport Office because of the quality of the identification photo supplied in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","41612"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531480","Home Office","false","2016-07-11","<p>Data on false documents identified by the Home Office within the border and immigration system shows that from 1 April 2014 to 31 March 2015 555 travel documents were identified that involved some form of photo substitution, including hard photo substitution, digital image substitution or substituted biographical data page. 25 of these cases involved UK passports.</p><p>In the period 1 April 2015 to 31 March 2016, 643 travel documents were identified that involved some form of photo substitution, including hard photo substitution, digital image substitution or substituted biographical data page. 18 of these cases involved UK passports.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-07-11T16:23:57.41Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531480/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531480/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531480/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-01","Passports: Photographs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many passports were reported as containing fake identification photos in the (a) last and (b) previous 12 months.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","41614"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531481","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-07","Proposals to improve the Strategic Road Network post-2020 will be considered as we prepare the second Road Investment Strategy – which was announced at Budget 2016. As part of the evidence-gathering process, Highways England is revisiting its Route Strategies to examine issues right across the Network. MPs and stakeholders are encouraged to engage with the process. Any specific proposals to address issues identified, such as additional junctions, will need to be prioritised and represent good value for money.","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-07-07T14:45:42.873Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531481/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531481/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531481/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-01","M1: Nottinghamshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of a new Junction 25A on the M1.","false","Biography information for Maggie Throup","Erewash","Maggie Throup","41602"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531482","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-06","<p>The Department has received a copy of the report, and was also involved in an earlier IPPR North stakeholder consultation workshop. The report is a potentially useful contribution to the evidence base for the Northern Powerhouse, as well as the Government’s and Transport for the North’s joint Northern Transport Strategy.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-07-06T10:56:46.607Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531482/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531482/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531482/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-01","Ports: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department has received a copy of the report by IPPR North, entitled Gateways to the northern powerhouse: A northern ports strategy, published in June 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","41605"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531483","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-07","<p>The Government is taking a number of steps to support the UK freight sector. These include working to address the LGV Driver shortage by increasing the supply of tests, speed up processing of licence applications and supporting the development of new apprenticeship standards; supporting the development of cleaner vehicles through our Low Carbon Truck trial and improving efficiency and reducing journey numbers through our Longer Semi-Trailer trial.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is also investing record amounts in the rail network in this Control Period and beyond. As part of the £38bn investment in the network as a whole, the Strategic Freight Network fund is providing £235.9 million to 2019 to deliver key infrastructure improvements to support the growth of the rail freight sector. I am committed to supporting the growth of rail freight in the UK and have therefore been working with the industry to develop a Rail Freight Strategy, which will set out our shared vision for the future.</p><p> </p><p>The Government also provides assistance to the freight industry through the Mode Shift Revenue Support Scheme and the Waterborne Freight Grant scheme, which encourage modal shift from road to rail or water where the costs are higher than road, and where there are environmental benefits to be gained.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-07-07T14:49:52.603Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531483/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531483/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531483/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-01","Freight","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps the Government is taking to support the UK freight sector.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","41606"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531484","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-06","<p>Universal Jobmatch is a self-service job posting service available to all employers. The service does not distinguish between registered or unregistered charities.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-07-06T12:14:17.767Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531484/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531484/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531484/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-01","Vacancies: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what his Department's policy is on allowing unregistered charities to advertise vacancies on Universal Jobmatch.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","41594"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531485","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-06","<p>The information requested is not available.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-07-06T12:16:35.867Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531485/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531485/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531485/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-01","Vacancies: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many unregistered charities are registered and able to post vacancies on Universal Jobmatch.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","41595"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530641","Attorney General","false","2016-07-07","<p>(a) The prosecution case was that Gurpal Virdi was the arresting officer. When the file was received from the police in November 2013, before charge, it contained a document which stated the date of birth of the complainant.</p><p> </p><p>(b) DC Markwick is named on the extract of the court’s memorandum of conviction dated 24 June 1987 in the section “name of informant or complainant”. The CPS did not request a statement from Mr Markwick. The prosecution case was that Gurpal Virdi was the arresting officer.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2016-07-07T09:02:55.747Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530641/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530641/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530641/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-06-30","Gurpal Virdi","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, pursuant to the Ministerial Correction of 24 June 2016 to Question 40180, on Gurpal Virdi, (a) when the Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) became aware that the Metropolitan Police had documentary evidence of the age of the complainant arrested on 7 November 1986 by PC Markwick and (b) whether the CPS asked for a statement by the arresting officer.","false","Biography information for Sir Peter Bottomley","Worthing West","Sir Peter Bottomley","41555"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530642","Attorney General","false","2016-07-07","<p>The Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) does not consider it possible to answer questions (a) and (b) with a number because of the degree of interpretation required to determine what may amount to a “contradiction” and what may be described materially as a “statement of fact”.</p><p>There are no contemporaneous documents from 1986. The memorandum of conviction, which is held in the form of a certified extract created some years later, contains the date of birth. The microfiche records, which are dated after 1986, also contain the date of birth.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2016-07-07T09:04:08.057Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530642/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530642/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530642/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-06-30","Gurpal Virdi","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, pursuant to the Ministerial Correction of 24 June 2016 to Question 40180, on Gurpal Virdi, how many statements of fact by the complainant were contradicted by (a) Tom Makins and (b) police or court records; and which police or court records confirmed the age of the complainant in November 1986.","false","Biography information for Sir Peter Bottomley","Worthing West","Sir Peter Bottomley","41556"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530643","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-07","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring that the UK remains open for business and continues to grow and thrive. On the domestic front <em>we’re investing in boosting the skills of the workforce by increasing the quality and quantity of apprenticeships in England, to reach a commitment of 3 million new apprenticeship starts by 2020. An apprenticeship levy will be introduced from April 2017 to encourage employers to invest in the skills they need. But, </em>as my Rt hon Friend the Prime Minister has said, there will be no immediate changes as a result of the EU referendum, including in the circumstances of EEA citizens living and working in the UK and our visa policies for non-EEA nationals. Ensuring our new relationship with the EU works for business and other employers is a priority for my Department in the months ahead.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-07-07T15:33:04.187Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530643/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530643/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530643/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-30","Skilled Workers: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU on the ability of firms to recruit skilled workers.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","41525"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530644","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-05","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Cabinet Office has established a new unit to oversee arrangements for the UK’s exit from the EU, after we have triggered Article 50. Until then, the UK remains a full member of the EU. The Government is reviewing trade policy, although the direction of future UK trade policy would be a matter for the new administration to consider once a new Prime Minister has been appointed.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","41527","2016-07-05T15:12:30.977Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530644/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530644/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530644/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-30","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate his Department has made of (a) the number of free trade and other agreements which the UK will need to renegotiate as a result of the outcome of the EU referendum and (b) the resources which will be required to renegotiate such agreements.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","41526"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530645","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-05","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Cabinet Office has established a new unit to oversee arrangements for the UK’s exit from the EU, after we have triggered Article 50. Until then, the UK remains a full member of the EU. The Government is reviewing trade policy, although the direction of future UK trade policy would be a matter for the new administration to consider once a new Prime Minister has been appointed.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","41526","2016-07-05T15:12:31.04Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530645/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530645/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530645/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-30","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of the outcome of the EU referendum on the Government's ability to negotiate trade agreements.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","41527"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530646","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-08","<p>The Accelerated Access Review team is a joint unit between the Department of Health and the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills. The Accelerated Access Review is intended to reform the landscape for the assessment, adoption and reimbursement of innovative drugs, devices and other treatments across all therapeutic areas.</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-07-08T11:00:54.123Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530646/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530646/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530646/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-30","Medical Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what engagement his Department has had with the Accelerated Access Review (AAR); and whether the AAR plans to investigate expediting the delivery of new drugs and devices to tackle MRSA and antimicrobial resistance.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","41572"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530647","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-11","<p>Yes.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-07-11T08:44:27.69Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530647/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530647/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530647/answer","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530647/answer/previousversion/5927","Biography information for Matt Hancock","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-30","Iraq Committee of Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will make arrangements for opposition party leaders or their nominated representatives to be granted advance sight of the conclusions of the Chilcot Report prior to that Report's publication.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","41592"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530648","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-07","<p>There are currently over 40 civil servants across Government working as one team dedicated to trade policy, for example in the UK Permanent Representation to the EU in Brussels, the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills, the Department for International Development, and the Foreign and Commonwealth Office. In addition, officials based in other government departments and agencies, whose roles are not trade specific, are regularly involved in working on trade-related issues as appropriate.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-07-07T15:29:05.323Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530648/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530648/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530648/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-30","EU Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many Government officials with trade negotiating skills are currently based in Brussels.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","41516"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530649","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-04","<p>Oliver Robbins has been appointed as the head of the new EU Unit in the Cabinet Office. He will have responsibility for supporting Cabinet in the examination of options for our future relationship outside the EU, with Europe, and the rest of the world as well as responsibility for the wider European and Global Issues Secretariat.</p><p> </p>","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin",,"2016-07-04T16:40:37.737Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530649/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530649/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530649/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-30","Cabinet Office EU Unit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether the European and Global Issues Secretariat is part of the new EU Unit; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","41517"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530650","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-07","<p>The Cabinet Office has established a new unit to oversee arrangements for the UK’s exit from the EU, after we have triggered Article 50. Until then, the UK remains a full member of the EU. The Government is reviewing trade policy, although the direction of future UK trade policy would be a matter for the new administration to consider once a new Prime Minister has been appointed.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-07-07T15:30:41.35Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530650/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530650/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530650/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-30","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the Government's (a) expertise and (b) capacity to carry out trade deals as a result of the outcome of the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","41518"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530651","Department for International Trade","false","2016-11-25","<p>I apologise for the time it has taken to answer the hon Member’s question UIN 41519. This was due to an administrative error.</p><p>I refer the hon Member for West Bromwich East to the answer I gave to the hon Member for Bristol West 13 October 2016, UIN: 46432.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","53620","2016-11-25T12:31:29.643Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530651/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530651/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530651/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-06-30","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what assessment he has made of the Government's capability of negotiating trade agreements.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","41519"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530652","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-04","<p>The unit will focus on delivering the outcome of the referendum, advising on transitional issues and exploring objectively options for our future relationship with Europe and the rest of the world from outside the EU.</p>","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin",,"2016-07-04T16:37:59.84Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530652/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530652/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530652/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-30","Cabinet Office EU Unit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps he plans to take to ensure that attracting trade and investment into the UK will be a key priority of the new EU unit.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","41507"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530653","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-05","<p>The Prime Minister has said that the unit will be staffed by the best and brightest from across the Civil Service. One of the tasks of the unit is to identify further requirements for expertise from outside the civil service and to begin the relevant recruitment and contracting processes.</p>","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin",,"2016-07-05T09:53:41.297Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530653/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530653/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530653/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-30","Cabinet Office EU Unit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps he plans to take to ensure that the new EU Unit recruits people with an appropriate level of expertise.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","41521"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530654","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-05","<p>We must ensure that the interests of all parts of our United Kingdom are protected and advanced. As we prepare for a new negotiation with the European Union, we will fully involve the Scottish Government, Welsh Government and Northern Ireland Executive. The exact shape of these discussions will be determined by the next Prime Minister.</p>","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin",,"2016-07-05T06:42:17.207Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530654/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530654/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530654/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-30","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps the Government plans to take to ensure that there is cross-party input into discussions with the devolved parliamentary bodies and administration in the process of negotiating the UK exit from the EU.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","41505"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530655","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-06","<p>Decisions on the mechanisms for negotiating the future of the UK's relationship with the EU are a matter for the next Prime Minister and the next Cabinet. It is a matter for Parliament to decide what structures it uses for holding that Government to account as the negotiations move forward.</p><p>It will also be important to ensure that the interests of all parts of the United Kingdom are protected and advanced.</p>","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin",,"2016-07-06T12:31:04.977Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530655/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530655/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530655/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-30","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to the Prime Minister's oral statement of 27 June 2016, Official Report, column 23, what steps the Government plans to take to ensure cross-party input at each stage of formulating national goals and strategy.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","41501"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530656","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-11","<p>Plans are in place for the creation of multi-departmental government Hubs in strategic locations outside London. These will further consolidate our office estate, whilst helping to attract and retain staff by stronger collaboration between departments and enabling staff to grow careers locally.</p><p> </p><p>We are consolidating our estate in central London and, since 2010, have reduced the number of offices from 181 to 54. Rationalisation will continue, enabling more multi-departmental use of HQ buildings and civil servant moves to peripheries where property costs are lower.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-07-11T08:25:16.507Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530656/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530656/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530656/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-30","Government Departments: Location","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps he is taking to encourage Government-funded agencies and departments to move their offices outside London.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","41502"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530657","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-07","<p>A total for advertising spend specifically could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-07-07T09:43:35.447Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530657/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530657/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530657/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-30","Cabinet Office: Advertising","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much his Department has spent on advertising in the last six months.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","41554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530658","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-07","<p>The Prime Minister has spoken to the First Ministers of Scotland and Wales, as well as the First and deputy First Ministers in Northern Ireland.</p><p>We must ensure that the interests of all parts of our United Kingdom are protected and advanced. So as we prepare for a new negotiation with the European Union, we will fully involve the Scottish Government, Welsh Government and Northern Ireland Executive.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose",,"2016-07-07T12:58:09.22Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530658/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530658/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530658/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-30","Brexit: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what discussions he has had with the Scottish Government on the outcome of the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","41567"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530659","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-06","<p>The Point of Light award recognises outstanding individual volunteers, who are making a change in their community and inspiring others. It was set up in partnership with US Points of Light with the personal support of original founder, President George HW Bush and current US President Barack Obama. Since the UK launch in April 2014, the Prime Minister has recognised over 570 people from all over the United Kingdom for their remarkable service. Award winners receive a personal letter from the Prime Minister, a certificate, a tweet from the official PM account and where possible some local media coverage including the local MP, regardless of political party.</p><p>Points of Light are also connected with each other to share best practice and increasingly work together to have even greater impact in our communities. The costs of the award are minimal but not held centrally.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-07-06T15:46:54.493Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530659/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530659/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530659/answer","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530659/answer/previousversion/5933","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-30","Voluntary Work: Prizes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps his Department is taking to promote the Prime Minister's Points of Light awards; and how much was spent (a) overall and (b) on staff costs related to the distribution of those awards in each year since their launch.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","41549"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530660","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-11","<p>It is too early following the EU referendum to make a detailed assessment of its impact on the future recruitment levels of Civil Servants.</p><p>Earlier this year, departments published their Single Departmental Plans (SDPs), setting out the key programmes of work required to deliver the Government’s Manifesto commitments. Departments have been developing plans to ensure they have the workforce required to deliver their SDPs, and this has not changed following the referendum.</p><p>Inevitably, leaving the EU will impact on the shape, size, skills and type of workforce we need but it is important that we understand our future workforce requirements and plan for these in a considered, coordinated and consistent manner across the Civil Service. The Cabinet Office is playing, and will continue to, play, a key role in facilitating this across the Civil Service.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-07-11T08:30:19.42Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530660/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530660/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530660/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-30","Civil Servants: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of the outcome of the EU referendum on future levels of recruitment of civil servants.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","41528"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530661","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-08","<p>As the Prime Minister said to the House on 27 June, we must ensure that the interests of all parts of our United Kingdom are protected and advanced.</p><p>We are already in contact with the Scottish, Welsh and Northern Ireland governments as we prepare for a new negotiation with the European Union.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose",,"2016-07-08T13:26:47.67Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530661/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530661/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530661/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-30","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment the Government has made of the potential effect of the outcome of the EU referendum on the future of the Union of the UK.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","41529"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530662","HM Treasury","false","2016-07-08","<p>While it is clear that we do now face a significant economic challenge as a result of the referendum decision, the UK economy is well placed to respond. Over the last six years we have taken a series of difficult, sometimes painful decisions in order to rebuild our economy.</p><p> </p><p>To minimise the risk to the economy in general, and make the decision work for the UK, we need to ensure that we resolve the economic uncertainty by working together to determine the model for our new relationship with the EU.</p><p> </p><p>Before the referendum campaign, the UK government published short-term and long-term assessments of the likely impact on the economy of the UK leaving the EU.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-07-08T11:22:53.157Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530662/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530662/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530662/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-30","Economic Situation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the economic effect of the outcome of the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","41530"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530663","HM Treasury","false","2016-07-08","<p>As the governor of the Bank of England said, the referendum result is as expected likely to lead to a significant negative shock for the British economy. Since the referendum there has been no new assessment of predicted levels of employment.</p><p> </p><p>Before the referendum campaign, the UK government published a short term assessment of predicted levels of employment of the UK leaving the EU.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-07-08T12:18:49.953Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530663/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530663/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530663/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-30","Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made on the potential effect on levels of employment of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","41533"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530664","HM Treasury","false","2016-07-08","<p>As the governor of the Bank of England said, the referendum result is as expected likely to lead to a significant negative shock for the British economy. Since the referendum there has been no assessment of predicted inflation broken down by sector.</p><p> </p><p>The trade – weighted value of the pound sterling has fallen by 11.5% since June 23<sup>rd</sup>.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-07-08T11:23:48.06Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530664/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530664/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530664/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-30","Cost of Living","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made on the potential effect of the outcome of the EU referendum on the cost of (a) household products, (b) food and (c) cars.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","41531"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530665","HM Treasury","false","2016-07-08","<p>The Office for Budget Responsibility will produce a revised forecast for the UK public finances in the autumn, which will take account of the UK’s decision to leave the EU.</p><p> </p><p>Before the referendum campaign, the UK government published short term and long term economic forecasts of the potential effect on government income of the UK leaving the EU</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-07-08T12:18:03.13Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530665/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530665/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530665/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-30","Public Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate the Government has made on the potential effect on government income of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","41532"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530666","HM Treasury","false","2016-07-06","<p>By governing the taxation of cross-border income flows in a predictable manner and eliminating double taxation and excessive taxation, tax treaties promote international trade and investment, leading to sustainable tax revenues, which are vital in financing development.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-07-06T11:24:34.987Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530666/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530666/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530666/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-30","Taxation: Malawi","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect of the UK-Malawi tax treaty on work to alleviate poverty and support economic growth in Malawi.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","41520"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530667","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-07-06","<p>It is too early to tell. We are keeping markets under review and are actively engaged with house builders. DCLG Ministers met with industry leaders last week to listen to their views in light of the EU referendum result.</p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-07-06T16:10:01.25Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530667/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530667/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530667/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-06-30","Housing: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the outcome of the EU referendum on house prices.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","41535"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530668","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-07","<p>As my right hon. Friend the Prime Minister has made clear, while the UK remains a member of the EU, current EU funding arrangements continue unchanged. It will be for the Government under the new Prime Minister to begin the negotiation to leave, and set out arrangements for those currently in receipt of EU funds.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-07-07T14:46:18.2Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530668/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530668/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530668/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-30","EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment the Government has made on the potential effect of the outcome of the EU referendum on EU development funding for the regions of England.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","41534"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530669","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-07-05","<p>This matter is being handled by International Military Services Limited (IMS). Negotiations are commerically sensitive and a confidentital matter between IMS and the Iranians.</p><p>The UK Government does not dispute the outcome of court hearings on this matter, but the current EU sanctions against the Iranian Ministry of Defence remain in force.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","41566","2016-07-05T15:02:21.423Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530669/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530669/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530669/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-30","Iran: Tanks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what estimate his Department has made of the amount owed by the Government to the government of Iran for Chieftain tanks bought by that government but never delivered; and if he will take steps to return that amount to the government of Iran.","false","Biography information for Bob Stewart","Beckenham","Bob Stewart","41562"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530670","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-07-05","<p>No records are held of Chieftain tanks being sold to the Government of Iraq.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","41564 ; 41565","2016-07-05T15:01:23.327Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530670/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530670/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530670/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-30","Iran: Tanks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether Chieftain tanks sold to the government of Iran but which remained undelivered were later sold to the government of Iraq.","false","Biography information for Bob Stewart","Beckenham","Bob Stewart","41563"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530671","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-07-05","<p>No records are held of Chieftain tanks being sold to the Government of Iraq.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","41563 ; 41565","2016-07-05T15:01:23.39Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530671/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530671/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530671/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-30","Iran: Tanks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what information his Department holds on the use during the Iran-Iraq war of Chieftain tanks sold by the UK to the government of Iraq; and whether those tanks had previously been purchased by the government of Iran.","false","Biography information for Bob Stewart","Beckenham","Bob Stewart","41564"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530672","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-07-05","<p>No records are held of Chieftain tanks being sold to the Government of Iraq.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","41563 ; 41564","2016-07-05T15:01:23.453Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530672/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530672/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530672/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-30","Iran: Tanks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether funds were received into the public purse from the sale of the same Chieftain tanks to Iraq which had already been sold through International Military Services but never delivered to the government of Iran.","false","Biography information for Bob Stewart","Beckenham","Bob Stewart","41565"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530673","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-07-05","<p>This matter is being handled by International Military Services Limited (IMS). Negotiations are commerically sensitive and a confidentital matter between IMS and the Iranians.</p><p>The UK Government does not dispute the outcome of court hearings on this matter, but the current EU sanctions against the Iranian Ministry of Defence remain in force.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","41562","2016-07-05T15:02:21.503Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530673/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530673/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530673/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-30","Iran: Tanks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what plans his Department has to return the funds owed to the government of Iran for the purchase of Chieftain tanks through International Military Services which were never delivered.","false","Biography information for Bob Stewart","Beckenham","Bob Stewart","41566"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530674","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-07-05","<p>In the main, defence requirements for steel are sourced by our prime contractors taking into account cost, time and quality. The Ministry of Defence complies with Cabinet Office guidance on steel procurement and works closely with contractors to ensure supply of steel products.</p><p>While defence steel requirements are relatively small, UK suppliers have already provided significant quantities of steel for our biggest defence procurement programmes. We are also positively encouraging bids from British companies to make sure they are in the best possible position to win future contracts.</p><p> </p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-07-05T15:03:05.377Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530674/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530674/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530674/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-30","Armed Forces: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment his Department has made of the contribution of steel production to the resources of the armed forces.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","41506"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530675","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-07-07","<p>We remain committed to operations and missions around the world as a strong and reliable ally. We will continue to play our part in countering Daesh; working with allies and partners on migration operations in the Aegean and Mediterranean; and supporting nations such as Afghanistan in their fight against terrorism.</p><p>We will continue to be a leading member of NATO; we are a permanent member of the UN Security Council; a member of the Commonwealth, the Organisation for Security and Cooperation in Europe, the Northern Group in Europe, the Five Power Defence Arrangements in the Far East, and the Five Eyes arrangements; and, we have strong and valued bilateral relationships in the Defence and security field with countries around the world. The EU Referendum does not change this.</p>","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier","41537","2016-07-07T14:32:16.537Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530675/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530675/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530675/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-30","NATO","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect of the outcome of the EU referendum on the UK's role in NATO.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","41536"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530676","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-07-07","<p>We remain committed to operations and missions around the world as a strong and reliable ally. We will continue to play our part in countering Daesh; working with allies and partners on migration operations in the Aegean and Mediterranean; and supporting nations such as Afghanistan in their fight against terrorism.</p><p>We will continue to be a leading member of NATO; we are a permanent member of the UN Security Council; a member of the Commonwealth, the Organisation for Security and Cooperation in Europe, the Northern Group in Europe, the Five Power Defence Arrangements in the Far East, and the Five Eyes arrangements; and, we have strong and valued bilateral relationships in the Defence and security field with countries around the world. The EU Referendum does not change this.</p>","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier","41536","2016-07-07T14:32:16.613Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530676/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530676/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530676/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-30","Islamic State","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment the Government has made of the effect of the outcome of the EU referendum on the UK's ability to work with allies in Syria and Iraq to fight Daesh.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","41537"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530677","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-07-05","<p>UK industry, as a whole, will build around 15 per cent by value of each of the more than 3,000 planned F-35s.</p><p>We expect the F-35B Lightning II Programme to sustain thousands of jobs in the UK into the 2040s, with many companies involved in design, manufacture and support of the aircraft, including at BAE Systems in Samlesbury. These jobs will enable the UK to retain and continue to develop its leading edge technologies and manufacturing capabilities, making a significant contribution to the UK economy.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-07-05T16:00:09.317Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530677/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530677/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530677/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-30","Joint Strike Fighter Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what estimate he has made of the number of jobs that will be supported at BAE Systems in Samlesbury by the F-35 programme; and for how long those jobs will be supported.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","41579"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530678","Department for Education","false","2016-07-05","<p>We want young people to have opportunities to engage with employers and the world of work throughout their education. This should be an age appropriate approach which begins with work discovery activities in primary school.</p><p>We recognise that older children will benefit from an increasing range of employer interventions including inspiring talks, mentoring and work experience. That is why the employer-led Careers &amp; Enterprise Company is increasing the level of employer input into schools and colleges. For example, by rolling out its Enterprise Adviser Network, which works closely with Local Enterprise Partnerships to connect employees from firms of all sizes to schools through a network of volunteer enterprise advisers drawn from business.</p><p>We want more young people to have the opportunity to take part in high quality work experience that helps to prepare them for the workplace and develop the employability skills that employers require. Work experience and work placements should be an integral part of most students’ 16-19 study programmes.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-07-05T13:44:06.703Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530678/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530678/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530678/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-06-30","Work Experience","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps her Department is taking to encourage employers to provide work experience opportunities to people in full-time education.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","41558"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530679","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-07-05","<p>In 2013/14, 4.51 million tonnes of woody biomass were used to generate electricity. 32% of this was from UK sources, 68% was imported. We do not hold data on the number of trees felled each year for use as biofuel, or the number of trees planted each year to be used as biofuel.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","41578","2016-07-05T16:28:28.837Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530679/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530679/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530679/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-06-30","Biofuels","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what estimate she has made of the number of trees that have been felled to be used as biofuel or biomass in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","41523"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530680","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-07-05","<p>In 2013/14, 4.51 million tonnes of woody biomass were used to generate electricity. 32% of this was from UK sources, 68% was imported. We do not hold data on the number of trees felled each year for use as biofuel, or the number of trees planted each year to be used as biofuel.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","41523","2016-07-05T16:28:28.903Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530680/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530680/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530680/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-06-30","Biofuels","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what estimate she has made of the number of trees that have been planted to be used in biofuel or biomass in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","41578"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530681","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-07-08","<p>No Government Grant-in-Aid funding for flood defence projects comes from the European Union. Where EU Structural Funds are being used in partnership funding, current arrangements for such funding will remain in place until we leave the EU.</p><p> </p><p>Defra will continue to ensure that the right policies are in place to reduce the risk of flooding and coastal erosion.</p><p> </p><p>The priorities for negotiating our exit from the EU will be a matter for the new Prime Minister and their Cabinet.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-07-08T12:59:32.627Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530681/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530681/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530681/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-06-30","Flood Control: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment the Government has made of the potential effect of the outcome of the EU referendum on flood defence funding.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","41538"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530682","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-07-08","<p>The Prime Minister made clear that there needs to be a system of agricultural support in the event of the UK leaving the EU.</p><p>The precise nature of any future domestic agricultural policy will be a matter for a new Prime Minister and their Cabinet.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-07-08T14:00:45.847Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530682/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530682/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530682/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-06-30","Agriculture: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will make it her policy to make available funding at the same level as currently received from the Common Agricultural Policy in the event of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","41551"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530683","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-07","<p>We have not had any discussions with US or EU counterparts on this issue.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-07-07T13:46:40.35Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530683/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530683/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530683/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-30","Palestinian Authority: Corruption","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his counterparts in (a) the USA and (b) the EU on corruption in the Palestinian authority.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Mr Nigel Dodds","41570"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530684","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-08","<p>As the Prime Minister, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron) has said, Britain is a truly great country that will always be capable of thriving and prospering on the world stage. We are a member of the UN Security Council, of NATO, the Commonwealth, of the G7 and the G20. Our voice will always be prominent.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-07-08T13:42:34.653Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530684/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530684/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530684/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-30","Diplomatic Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of the outcome of the EU referendum on the Government's global diplomatic standing.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","41539"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530685","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-07","We pay close attention to the human rights situation in China and remain concerned by all reports of restrictions to freedom of religion or belief and persecution of faith groups. The full range of our human rights concerns in China are set out in the Foreign and Commonwealth Office’s Annual Report on Human Rights and Democracy, most recently published on 21 April. The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond), has continued to raise concerns about the detention of human rights lawyers, a number of whom have represented clients who have been punished for exercising their freedom of religious belief. He did so with both Foreign Minister Wang Yi in January and President Zhou Qiang of the Supreme People’s Court last month.","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-07-07T14:01:34.54Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530685/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530685/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530685/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-30","China: Religious Freedom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has made to the government of China on the persecution of Christians and other faith groups.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Mr Nigel Dodds","41584"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530686","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-05","<p>We have not made any respresentations to the Israeli authorities on this issue.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-07-05T15:51:05.117Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530686/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530686/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530686/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-30","Israel: Prisons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, with reference to the recommendations of the UN Committee against Torture Review of Israel, adopted on 12 May 2016 by that Committee, what representations he has made to his Israeli counterpart on transferring responsibility for prisoner healthcare to that country's Ministry of Health.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","41590"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530687","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-05","<p>Whilst we have not made any representations on this specific detention, our Embassy in Tel Aviv regularly raises concerns about detention, including Israel's extensive use of administrative detention. These concerns were raised with the Israeli authorities most recently on 27 June. Administrative detention should, according to international law, be used only when security makes it absolutely necessary rather than as routine practice, and as a preventative rather than a punitive measure. We continue to call on the Israeli authorities to comply with their obligations under international law, and either charge or release detainees.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-07-05T15:53:50.307Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530687/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530687/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530687/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-30","Eteraf Al-Rimawi","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to the government of Israel on the (a) immediate release or (b) prompt charge and fair trial of Eteraf Al-Rimawi.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","41591"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530688","Department of Health","false","2016-07-05","<p>A 12-week public consultation, asking for views on how to successfully implement the reforms, closed on the 30 June 2016. The Government is currently considering submissions from interested parties to the consultation and will publish a response in due course.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-07-05T15:37:21.027Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530688/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530688/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530688/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-30","Health Professions: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will withdraw his proposal to replace bursaries for nurses, midwives and allied health professionals with student loans.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","41588"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530689","Department of Health","false","2016-07-05","<p>The Department is currently working on plans for how best to distribute the £1.5 million of funding for child prosthetics and will set out comprehensive details once the plans are finalised.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-07-05T16:16:17.967Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530689/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530689/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530689/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-30","Prosthetics: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to the announcement in paragraph 1.97 of the March 2016 Budget, on funding for child prosthetics, (a) by what mechanisms people can access, (b) who is able to apply for, (c) what the criteria is for accessing, (d) how many people have received and (e) who is responsible for distributing such funding.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","41561"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530690","Department of Health","false","2016-07-05","<p>Nothing will change overnight as a result of the European Union referendum decision. The United Kingdom remains a member of the EU until Article 50 negotiations have concluded. This could take up to two years or more if negotiations are extended. EU law continues to apply and ongoing compliance with EU law is considered important in facilitating orderly transition, for negotiating purposes, and to offer certainty in the meantime. As long as the UK is subject to EU law, the present arrangements remain in place.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-07-05T13:20:32.157Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530690/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530690/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530690/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-30","Neuromuscular Disorders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of the outcome of the EU referendum on continued access to emerging treatments for muscular dystrophy and other rare neuromuscular conditions.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","41576"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530691","Department of Health","false","2016-07-08","<p>No such discussions have taken place.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-07-08T09:54:20.617Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530691/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530691/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530691/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-30","WHO Framework Convention on Tobacco Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions he has had with his Ministerial colleagues on Article 5.3 of the WHO Framework on Tobacco Control.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","41522"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530692","Department of Health","false","2016-07-07","<p>Health Ministers have held no meetings with the tobacco industry to discuss illicit trade.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-07-07T13:25:46.99Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530692/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530692/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530692/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-30","Tobacco: Smuggling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent discussions he has had with the tobacco industry on the Government's commitment to tackle the illicit trade in tobacco products and its potential effect on public health policy.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","41509"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530693","Department of Health","false","2016-07-08","<p>I recently discussed the impact of illicit trade of tobacco on public health as part of the Cross Government Ministerial Group on Illicit Trade, which was announced in the refreshed Government strategy ‘Tackling illicit tobacco: from leaf to light’ last year.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-07-08T09:55:22.03Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530693/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530693/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530693/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-30","Tobacco: Smuggling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions he has had with his ministerial colleagues on the potential effect of the Government's commitment to tackle the illicit trade in tobacco products on public health policy.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","41508"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530694","Department of Health","false","2016-07-06","<p>The Government Response to the Review of Choice in End of Life Care was published on 5 July 2016. The Response sets out a commitment for end of life care to ensure high quality, personalised care for everyone at the end of life and details the actions that the Government and the health and care system will be taking to deliver this.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-07-06T10:19:32.33Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530694/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530694/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530694/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-30","Choice in End of Life Care Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what progress has been made on the Government's response to the Choice Review; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dr Sarah Wollaston","Totnes","Dr Sarah Wollaston","41571"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530695","Home Office","false","2016-07-05","<p>The Immigration Act 2016 received Royal Assent on 12th May 2016. Provisions in the Act that create a mechanism to transfer responsibility for unaccompanied asylum seeking children from one local authority to another in England came into force on 31st May. Announcements about implementation of the other provisions mentioned and extensions to other parts of the UK will be made in due course once discussions with the Devolved Administrations have taken place. There has been no correspondence with Ministers of the Scottish Government relating to the Immigration Act 2016 since the Act received Royal Assent.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","41575","2016-07-05T13:40:50.753Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530695/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530695/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530695/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-06-30","Immigration Act 2016","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether she plans to extend or give effect to the provisions in the Immigration Act 2016 in respect of (a) residential tenancies, (b) transfer of responsibility for unaccompanied children and (c) limitations on local authority support for people who have been refused asylum, adult migrant care leavers and other migrants.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","41574"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530696","Home Office","false","2016-07-05","<p>Home Office Ministers have meetings with a wide variety of international partners, as well as organisations and individuals in the public and private sectors, as part of the process of policy development and delivery. Details of these meetings are passed to the Cabinet Office on a quarterly basis and are subsequently published on the Gov.uk website: http://data.gov.uk/dataset/ministerial-data-home-office</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-07-05T13:40:31.977Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530696/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530696/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530696/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-06-30","Tobacco: Smuggling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent discussions she has had with the tobacco industry on the Government's commitment to tackle the illicit trade in tobacco products.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","41557"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530697","Home Office","false","2016-07-11","<p>The UK currently remains part of the EU. As the Prime Minister has indicated, there will be no immediate changes for British citizens living in European countries or European citizens living in the UK and there will be no change to the way people travel.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-07-11T16:22:16.903Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530697/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530697/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530697/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-06-30","Migration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment her Department has made of the outcome of the EU referendum on levels of (a) inward and (b) outward migration.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","41543"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530698","Home Office","false","2016-07-07","<p>The Government remains committed to its leading role in working with the international community to tackle the migration crisis. The UK remains a member of the EU until negotiations are concluded and nothing changes overnight as a result of the referendum. We will maintain our contribution to Operation Sophia.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-07-07T12:32:15.617Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530698/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530698/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530698/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-06-30","Refugees: Europe","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment her Department has made of the effect of the outcome of the EU referendum on the Government's role in (a) tackling the refugee crisis in Europe and (b) Operation Sophia in the Mediterranean.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","41544"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530699","Home Office","false","2016-07-13","<p>Cooperation with our European partners has not ceased since the result of the referendum was announced. UK authorities continue to cooperate with their counterparts in other EU Member States bilaterally, including by using the Schengen Information System (SIS II), Europol, Eurojust, the European Arrest Warrant and other measures.</p><p>These tools, developed under the EU’s legislative framework, enable practical cooperation and information sharing, which is of value. However, much of our cooperation on counter-terrorism and national security matters sits outside of EU structures, including the Five Eyes, the closest international intelligence-sharing arrangement in the world, and the Counter Terrorism Group (CTG), a cooperation forum between the security services of EU Member States plus Norway and Switzerland, which sits outside EU law.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","41542","2016-07-13T13:35:26.387Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530699/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530699/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530699/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-06-30","Terrorism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment her Department has made of the potential effect of the outcome of the EU referendum on the Government's ability to tackle terrorism.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","41545"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530700","Home Office","false","2016-07-13","<p>Cooperation with our European partners has not ceased since the result of the referendum was announced. UK authorities continue to cooperate with their counterparts in other EU Member States bilaterally, including by using the Schengen Information System (SIS II), Europol, Eurojust, the European Arrest Warrant and other measures.</p><p>These tools, developed under the EU’s legislative framework, enable practical cooperation and information sharing, which is of value. However, much of our cooperation on counter-terrorism and national security matters sits outside of EU structures, including the Five Eyes, the closest international intelligence-sharing arrangement in the world, and the Counter Terrorism Group (CTG), a cooperation forum between the security services of EU Member States plus Norway and Switzerland, which sits outside EU law.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","41545","2016-07-13T13:35:26.323Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530700/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530700/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530700/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-06-30","National Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment her Department has made of the potential effect of the outcome of the EU referendum on national security.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","41542"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530701","Home Office","false","2016-07-13","For the time being, the United Kingdom remains part of the EU and there will be no immediate changes to our immigration system.","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-07-13T13:40:05.217Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530701/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530701/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530701/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-06-30","Immigration Controls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment the Government has made of the potential merits of introducing an Australian-style points immigration system.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","41540"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530702","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-08","<p>The True Vision reporting facility, which is owned by the National Police Chiefs’ Council, is designed to help victims access services and to increase the reporting of hate crime.</p><p>There were nine reports made through True Vision to Nottinghamshire Police in June 2016. Seven of these reports were submitted between 23<sup>rd</sup> and 30<sup>th </sup>June. True Vision does not record details of the location within the county.</p><p>True Vision reports also include both crime and non-crime hate incidents. Any form of hate crime is totally unacceptable and there are tough sentencing options available to the courts to deal with those who commit these crimes. We will continue to work with the police to increase reporting of these offences.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","41511 ; 41512","2016-07-08T14:48:26.807Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530702/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530702/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530702/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-06-30","Hate Crime: Nottinghamshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many incidents reported to the police online reporting portal True Vision in June 2016 took place in (a) Nottingham and (b) Nottinghamshire.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","41510"
