"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530711","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-07-07","<p>The Government is determined to do everything possible to get the best deal for all parts of the United Kingdom and to make sure that Northern Ireland’s interests are protected.</p><p>I will work with the Irish Government on our close shared interest of keeping the open border for people and business.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2016-07-07T10:14:16.667Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530711/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530711/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530711/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-06-30","Borders: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what assessment her Department has made of the potential effect of the outcome of the EU referendum on arrangements at the border between Ireland and Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","41541"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530712","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-07-07","<p>The Government will make sure that the interests of all parts of our United Kingdom are protected and advanced as we prepare for negotiations to exit the EU.</p><p>The Northern Ireland Executive, as well as other devolved administrations across the UK, will be fully involved in this process.</p><p>A new civil service EU unit has been created to support this process, bringing together officials and policy expertise from across the Civil Service and reporting to the whole of Cabinet on delivering the outcome of the referendum.</p><p>My officials will work closely with this team and with their counterparts in the Northern Ireland Civil Service and Irish Government officials.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers","41553","2016-07-07T10:17:59.17Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530712/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530712/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530712/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-06-30","Brexit: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what administrative arrangements have been made within her Department to respond to the result of the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Mr Nigel Dodds","41552"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530713","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-07-07","<p>The Government will make sure that the interests of all parts of our United Kingdom are protected and advanced as we prepare for negotiations to exit the EU.</p><p>The Northern Ireland Executive, as well as other devolved administrations across the UK, will be fully involved in this process.</p><p>A new civil service EU unit has been created to support this process, bringing together officials and policy expertise from across the Civil Service and reporting to the whole of Cabinet on delivering the outcome of the referendum.</p><p>My officials will work closely with this team and with their counterparts in the Northern Ireland Civil Service and Irish Government officials.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers","41552","2016-07-07T10:17:59.233Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530713/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530713/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530713/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-06-30","Brexit: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what arrangements she plans to put in place to ensure the best possible co-ordination between her Department and the Northern Ireland Executive in response to the result of the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Mr Nigel Dodds","41553"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530714","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-07-07","<p>No decisions have been taken about the future structure of the Electoral Office for Northern Ireland.</p><p>A full public consultation will take place later this year and the views of all stakeholders will be fully considered as part of the consultation and policy development process.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace","41573","2016-07-07T10:23:07.297Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530714/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530714/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530714/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-06-30","Electoral Register: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what assessment she has made of the potential effect of the proposed closures of electoral offices in Northern Ireland on voter registration and turnout.","false","Biography information for Tom Elliott","Fermanagh and South Tyrone","Tom Elliott","41568"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530715","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-07-08","<p>The Government had hoped to announce a decision on airports capacity this summer. Any announcement on airports capacity would have to be made with the House in session and we cannot foresee an announcement until at least October.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to delivering the important infrastructure projects it has set out, including delivering runway capacity on the timetable set out by the Airports Commission’s report.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2016-07-08T12:51:36.583Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530715/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530715/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530715/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-06-30","Aviation: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what recent assessment she has made of the effect on Northern Ireland of postponing the decision on extra runway capacity in South East England.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Mr Nigel Dodds","41569"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530716","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-07-07","<p>No decisions have been taken about the future structure of the Electoral Office for Northern Ireland.</p><p>A full public consultation will take place later this year and the views of all stakeholders will be fully considered as part of the consultation and policy development process.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace","41568","2016-07-07T10:23:07.343Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530716/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530716/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530716/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-06-30","Chief Electoral Officer for Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, with reference to the proposed closure of regional electoral offices in Northern Ireland, what steps she plans to take to ensure that all people in Northern Ireland will be able to continue to exercise their right to vote.","false","Biography information for Tom Elliott","Fermanagh and South Tyrone","Tom Elliott","41573"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530717","HM Treasury","false","2016-07-08","<p>As the Prime Minister has made clear, while the UK remains a member of the EU, current EU funding arrangements continue unchanged. It will be for the government under the new Prime Minister to begin the negotiation to exit the EU and set out the arrangements they will put in place for those currently in receipt of EU funds.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-07-08T11:21:51.597Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530717/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530717/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530717/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-30","EU Grants and Loans: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment the Government has made of the potential effect of the outcome of the EU referendum on EU development funding for Scotland.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","41546"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530718","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-05","<p>We expect to publish a new Accessibility Action Plan for consultation in late summer. We will publish the final plan when we have taken account of all the consultation responses received.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-07-05T10:50:50.167Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530718/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530718/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530718/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-06-30","Public Transport: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he plans to publish his accessibility action plan for public transport.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","41550"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530719","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-05","<p>The Department receives regular updates from the Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency (DVSA) on waiting times for practical driving tests.</p><p> </p><p>An important starting point is to recognise that the way the DVSA measure and report on waiting times is not as clear as it may seem to be. The official waiting time is based on more than 10% of test slots being available in an individual test centre. Whilst this approach is useful for planning it does not reflect the situation centre-by-centre across the country nor the availability of the one slot any candidate requires in order to take their test. If DVSA were to report on, for example, the average waiting time for the next available slot the waiting time would be on average, only 7.6 weeks.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-07-05T15:00:26.22Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530719/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530719/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530719/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-06-30","Driving Tests","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what reports his Department has received on differences between actual and published driving test waiting times in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Dame Louise Ellman","Liverpool, Riverside","Mrs Louise Ellman","41559"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530720","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-05","<p>The Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency (DVSA) has taken a number of steps to reduce driving test waiting times in the last 12 months. These include:</p><p> </p><ul><li>recruiting additional driving examiners. Last year, there were 193 new examiners who started work at various test centres across the country. This year DVSA has recruited another 48 examiners and made employment offers to another 110 people.</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li>Launching an initiative to offer additional hours to examiners over the summer months, including weekends and bank holidays. So far, a quarter of driving examiners have signed up to take part in this initiative to help bring waiting times down further.</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li>We recognise that more work needs to be done to drive down waiting times and we are investigating all avenues to do so.</li></ul>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-07-05T13:38:22.317Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530720/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530720/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530720/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-06-30","Driving Tests","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he has taken to reduce driving test waiting times in the last 12 months; and what data the Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency has collected to assess the effectiveness of such steps.","false","Biography information for Dame Louise Ellman","Liverpool, Riverside","Mrs Louise Ellman","41560"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530721","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-05","<p>The bus market outside London is deregulated and decisions regarding service provision is primarily a commercial matter for bus operators. Decisions on subsidised bus services are a matter for individual English local authorities, in the light of their other spending priorities.</p><p> </p><p>However, my Department provides around £40m of Bus Subsidy Operators Grant (BSOG) directly to English local authorities for local bus services, of which Lancashire receives almost £1.9 million. BSOG plays an especially important role in protecting services in rural areas by helping extend the bus network, providing residents with vital links to local services.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-07-05T10:49:51.157Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530721/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530721/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530721/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-06-30","Bus Services: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if his Department will make an assessment of the provision of bus services serving Sabden in Lancashire; and what steps his Department is taking to protect bus services serving rural communities.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","41524"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530722","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-05","<p>Britain has some of the world’s lowest road casualty rates. But, in line with our Manifesto commitment, we are determined to do more to make our roads even safer. The British Road Safety Statement, published on 21 December 2015, sets out the government’s priorities for action, including practical measures to help vulnerable groups stay safe on our roads, extra money to crackdown on drug drivers and tougher penalties for people using mobile phones while driving.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, whilst the Department for Transport has not conducted specific work with TfL on the Sarah Hope telephone line, the government does provide funding, via the Ministry of Justice, for support services for victims of road traffic collisions, including a national helpline and information packs.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-07-05T10:42:18.843Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530722/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530722/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530722/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-06-30","Transport for London: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what work his Department has conducted with Transport for London on the Sarah Hope Line.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","41548"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530723","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-05","<p>The official waiting time is based on more than 10% of test slots being available in an individual test centre. Whilst this approach is useful for planning it does not reflect the situation centre-by-centre across the country nor the availability of the one slot any candidate requires in order to take their test. If DVSA were to report on, for example, the average waiting time for the next available test slot, the waiting time would be shorter. The official measure currently shows a waiting time of more than 12 weeks; however, the next available test slot is, on average, only 7.6 weeks.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-07-05T13:39:58.213Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530723/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530723/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530723/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-06-30","Driving Tests","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent assessment he has made of the accuracy of the driving test waiting times published by the Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency.","false","Biography information for Dame Louise Ellman","Liverpool, Riverside","Mrs Louise Ellman","41577"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530724","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-05","<p>In line with our localism agenda, it would be for the local authority to consider whether a local rail scheme such as re-opening Chatburn station was a priority for them.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-07-05T10:40:29.747Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530724/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530724/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530724/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-06-30","Railway Stations: Ribble Valley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department has made an assessment of the viability of reopening Chatburn railway station in the Ribble Valley.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","41580"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530725","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-05","<p>UK Government projects such as the Local Sustainable Transport Fund, the recently announced Access Fund and the Cycling, Walking Investment Strategy demonstrate the government’s commitment to supporting sustainable travel initiatives which support local economies, boost economic growth and cut carbon emissions.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Devolution settlements provide the funding and the powers to enable the respective governments to decide on appropriate infrastructure investment in their administrations.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-07-05T11:18:47.117Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530725/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530725/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530725/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-06-30","Cycling and Public Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent steps the Government has taken to encourage the level of (a) public transport use and (b) cycling in (i) Northern Ireland and (b) other constituent parts of the UK.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","41585"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530726","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-05","<p>No such discussions have taken place. Decisions on taxation, including Air Passenger Duty, are of course a matter for HM Treasury.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-07-05T11:19:52.443Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530726/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530726/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530726/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-06-30","Air Passenger Duty: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent discussions he has had with the Northern Ireland Executive on proposals to reduce air passenger duty on short to medium haul flights.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","41586"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530727","Home Office","false","2016-07-07","<p>The Government has been clear that there will be no immediate changes in the circumstances of European nationals entering or currently residing in the UK.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-07-07T12:31:58.007Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530727/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530727/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530727/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-06-30","Aviation: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps she is taking to advise people in the UK of their continuing rights to travel freely within the EU.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","41587"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530728","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-05","<p>As set out in Information Paper E13 (Management of Traffic during Construction), HS2 Ltd has a policy of using rail to transport bulk excavated material over long distances, wherever reasonably practicable. In addition, the Secretary of State has provided an assurance to the London Borough of Camden and Transport for London to seek to maximise, as far as reasonably practicable, the movement of material by rail at Euston. A detailed study has been undertaken to explore how this could be achieved, which has highlighted a number of technical options which are currently being assessed with respect to the impact on passengers, the environmental and socio-economic impacts and impacts on the HS2 programme. An initial decision on how to proceed will be made following the completion of this assessment.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-07-05T10:45:56.84Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530728/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530728/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530728/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-06-30","Large Goods Vehicles: Camden","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to substantially reduce the number of heavy goods vehicles on the roads around Euston; and if he will make it his policy to encourage the use of rail to transport excavated and construction materials in that area during the development of High Speed 2.","false","Biography information for Keir Starmer","Holborn and St Pancras","Keir Starmer","41593"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530729","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-07","<p>Highways England is aiming to commence construction of the M1 J24 to J25 smart motorway scheme in 2016/17 with completion in 2017/18. M1 J23a to J24 is being developed and Highways England is currently committed to commencing construction on this section in 2019/20. Highways England is currently considering combining these works to ensure the most efficient and effective delivery and minimise disruption to the travelling public. Work continues on developing these proposals and in due course Highways England will be able to confirm the final programme for delivery of M1 J23a to J25.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-07-07T14:47:03.66Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530729/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530729/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530729/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-06-30","M1: East Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what progress has been made on plans in the Road Investment Strategy for a new smart motorway between junctions 23 and 25 of the M1.","false","Biography information for Maggie Throup","Erewash","Maggie Throup","41583"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530730","HM Treasury","false","2016-07-08","<p>As the Prime Minister has made clear, while the UK remains a member of the EU, current EU funding arrangements continue unchanged. It will be for the government under the new Prime Minister to begin the negotiation to exit the EU and set out the arrangements they will put in place for those currently in receipt of EU funds.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-07-08T11:20:34.56Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530730/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530730/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530730/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-30","EU Grants and Loans: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment the Government has made of the potential effect of the outcome of the EU referendum on EU development funding for Wales.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","41547"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530731","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-05","<p>Estimates of (a) pensioners and (b) children living in low income households in the North East of England are published in the National Statistics Households Below Average Income (HBAI) series. These are calculated on a three-year average basis as single year estimates are too volatile from year to year.</p><p>In the North East, the proportion of pensioners with incomes below 60% of median equivalised income, After Housing Costs, rose by 1ppt to 13% between 2011/12 – 2013/14 and 2012/13 – 2014/15, while the proportion of children with incomes below 60% of median equivalised income, Before Housing Costs, rose by 1ppt to 19% between 2011/12 – 2013/14 and 2012/13 – 2014/15.</p><p>The government has also set out a new life chances approach that will include a set of indicators to measure progress in tackling the root causes of poverty such as worklessness, educational attainment and family stability.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-07-05T13:47:34.283Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530731/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530731/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530731/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-06-30","Low Incomes: North East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what change there has been in the proportion of (a) pensioners and (b) children living in low income households in the North East of England in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","41589"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530732","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-07","<p>Under the Industrial Injuries Scheme people suffering from various dust-related diseases, including asbestos, may be able to receive a weekly disablement benefit, and can also apply for a lump sum payment. The Government believes this is the right approach, recognising a range of different circumstances, and taking account of life expectancy.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is currently developing an online service for Industrial Injuries Disablement Benefit. Initially this is for accident claims but it is intended to include industrial diseases at a later stage, providing service improvements and reducing the number of forms.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","41582","2016-07-07T12:56:52.59Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530732/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530732/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530732/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-06-30","Industrial Injuries Disablement Benefit: Asbestos","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if his Department will make an assessment of the potential merits of implementing a single asbestos disease-related benefit.","false","Biography information for Mhairi Black","Paisley and Renfrewshire South","Mhairi Black","41581"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530733","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-07","<p>Under the Industrial Injuries Scheme people suffering from various dust-related diseases, including asbestos, may be able to receive a weekly disablement benefit, and can also apply for a lump sum payment. The Government believes this is the right approach, recognising a range of different circumstances, and taking account of life expectancy.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is currently developing an online service for Industrial Injuries Disablement Benefit. Initially this is for accident claims but it is intended to include industrial diseases at a later stage, providing service improvements and reducing the number of forms.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","41581","2016-07-07T12:56:52.637Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530733/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530733/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530733/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-06-30","Industrial Injuries Disablement Benefit: Asbestos","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if his Department will take steps to reduce the number of forms associated with asbestos-related benefits.","false","Biography information for Mhairi Black","Paisley and Renfrewshire South","Mhairi Black","41582"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530734","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-07","<p>This is a matter for the new Prime Minister and their Cabinet. As the PM has said, we have now got to look at all the detailed arrangements, and Parliament will clearly have a role in making sure that we find the best way forward.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2016-07-07T15:45:49.507Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530734/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530734/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530734/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-30","Radicalism","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the consent of Parliament will be obtained to a new agreement governing the UK’s relationship with the EU.","false","Biography information for Lord Birt",,"Lord Birt","HL896"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530735","Department for International Development","false","2016-07-12","<p>The St Helena Line has no current plans for the Royal Mail Ship (RMS) St Helena to visit Tristan da Cunha.</p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2016-07-12T16:34:25.4Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530735/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530735/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530735/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-06-30","Capital Investment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the extension in service of the RMS St Helena, whether there are any plans for the ship to visit Tristan da Cunha.","false","Biography information for Lord Jones of Cheltenham",,"Lord Jones of Cheltenham","HL897"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530736","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-08","<p>Apprenticeships with a duration of less than 12 months are included in published statistics where the apprentice is 19 years or older on the day they start their apprenticeship and not all elements of the framework are being delivered. This could be because of Recognition of Prior Learning or previously certificated achievement of qualifications. In all cases, the minimum length of the apprenticeship is six months.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-07-08T11:28:50.187Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530736/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530736/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530736/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-30","Motor Sports: Wales","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Neville-Rolfe on 21 June (HL669), what are the exceptional conditions in which apprenticeships of less than 12 months are published in their statistics on apprenticeships.","false","Biography information for Baroness Corston",,"Baroness Corston","HL898"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530737","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-14","<p>Each prison’s staffing level is carefully designed to provide a safe, decent and secure environment for staff and prisoners. In March 2016 there were an extra 530 prison staff across the prison estate compared with January 2015; and NOMS will continue to recruit sufficient Prison Officers to support full delivery of the Benchmark in each establishment. A further £10 million has also been allocated to NOMS to specifically address safety concerns across the prison estate.</p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2016-07-14T14:41:29.64Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530737/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530737/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530737/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-06-30","Motor Sports: Wales","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the adequacy of the current staffing levels in UK prisons.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL899"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530738","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-14","<p>Her Majesty’s Chief Inspector of Prisons has a statutory duty to report to the Secretary of State for Justice on conditions in prisons, and the treatment of prisoners, in all prisons and young offender institutions in England and Wales. For each inspection completed, a report is published which includes recommendations for improvement. These reports are all in the public domain and available from the Inspectorate’s website. Inspections of prisons in Scotland and Northern Ireland are the responsibility of their respective inspection authorities.</p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2016-07-14T14:34:25.553Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530738/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530738/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530738/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-06-30","Motor Sports: Wales","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the Prisons Inspectorate has raised concerns about the conditions in any UK prisons in the past 12 months, and if so, which.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL900"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530739","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-14","<p>There are no plans to withdraw the contracts of any privately managed prisons.</p><p> </p><p>Privately-managed prisons have been a key feature of the prison estate for 20 years. Some of our best prisons are operated by private providers, and they will continue to play a crucial role in rehabilitating offenders.</p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2016-07-14T14:32:26.057Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530739/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530739/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530739/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-06-30","EU Satellite Centre","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they are considering withdrawing the contracts for responsibility for certain prisons from private companies, and if so, which companies.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL901"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530740","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-14","<p>The National Offender Management Service has a range of measures for monitoring fire safety in prisons. NOMS does not specifically monitor the number of arson incidents in prisons.</p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2016-07-14T14:17:33.08Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530740/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530740/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530740/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-06-30","Europol","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether any prisons have suffered arson attacks in the past 12 months.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL902"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530741","Department of Health","false","2016-07-07","<p>In general, if the hospital pharmacy issues medicines to a ward or individual patient and those medicines remain in the organisation, either because they are not supplied on discharge or the patient dies, then the medicines would be returned to ward stock or the pharmacy and re-used. If the medicines had been brought in to the hospital by the patient and the patient is subsequently discharged or dies, and the medicines remain in the hospital, then they would be safely disposed of by the hospital pharmacy.</p><p> </p><p>The main difference between the two scenarios is that, in the first there is sufficient guarantee of the storage conditions to ensure the medicines’ integrity can be assured. In the second scenario, such integrity cannot be guaranteed.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-07-07T12:57:22.3Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530741/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530741/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530741/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-30","Eurojust","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what happens to unused medication sealed and in date, in hospitals on the discharge or death of a patient.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL903"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530742","Home Office","false","2016-07-14","<p>The provision of legal resources in France is a matter for the French Government.</p><p>Asylum seekers cannot claim asylum in the UK if they are in France. If a person requires international protection they should claim asylum in France, which is bound by the same EU and international obligations as the UK.</p><p>If after claiming asylum in France it is established that the UK is the state responsible for examining their claim on the basis of the Dublin regulation, including under its family unity provisions, a take charge request may be submitted to the Home Office.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-07-14T12:44:37.063Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530742/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530742/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530742/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-06-30","European Union Agency for Fundamental Rights","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what legal resources are being provided to refugees in the camps in Calais and Dunkirk to make asylum applications to the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL904"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530743","Home Office","false","2016-07-12","<p>The timing of the publication of the Review of the Use and Retention of Custody Images is a decision to be taken by Ministers, in the context of other Parliamentary business. We plan to publish the Review shortly.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","HL906","2016-07-12T13:31:06.277Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530743/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530743/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530743/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-06-30","Agency for the Cooperation of Energy Regulators","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what legislation governs the retention of facial custody images.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL905"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530744","Home Office","false","2016-07-12","<p>The timing of the publication of the Review of the Use and Retention of Custody Images is a decision to be taken by Ministers, in the context of other Parliamentary business. We plan to publish the Review shortly.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","HL905","2016-07-12T13:31:06.383Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530744/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530744/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530744/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-06-30","European Banking Authority","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Bates on 14 March (HL6870), why the publication of the findings of the review of the retention of custody images is now over a year late.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL906"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530745","Home Office","false","2016-07-18","<p>The Biometrics Strategy is in its final stages of completion and we expect to publish it in due course. The Forensic Science Strategy was published on 11 March 2016.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-07-18T12:29:50.067Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530745/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530745/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530745/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-06-30","British Nationality","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the recommendation in the House of Commons Science and Technology Committee's report <i>Current and future uses of biometric data and technologies</i> (6th Report, Session 2014–15) that a comprehensive, cross-departmental forensics and biometrics strategy be published no later than December 2015, why such a strategy has not yet been published.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL907"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530746","Home Office","false","2016-07-14","<p>The UK is the largest bilateral contributor to the humanitarian response to the crisis in Europe and the Balkans with a total contribution of £65 million. The efforts of the partners we fund are targeted to reach the most vulnerable including children.</p><p>It also includes the £10 million Refugee Children Fund the Department for International Development (DFID) has created to support vulnerable refugee and migrant children specifically in Europe. The fund will support three specialist and mandated organisations; the UNHCR, Save the Children and the International Rescue Committee to work with host authorities to care for and assist unaccompanied or separated children in Europe and the Balkans.</p><p>In addtion, the government continues to implement the Immigration Act 2016, including the provision to transfer unaccompained refugee children to the UK from elswhere in Europe. We are consulting local authorities as required and are also working closely with relevant Member States and other partners such as UNHCR, UNICEF and Save the Children.</p><p>We continue to fulfil our obligations under the Dublin Regulation to unaccompanied children who qualify for transfer to the UK under family reunification provisions. Since January 2016 our records show that over 60 children have been transferred from other EU countries to the UK.</p><p>We are working with UNHCR on our Children at Risk Resettlement Scheme to resettle vulnerable children, both unaccompanied and with their family members from the Middle East and North Africa region. We have committed to resettling several hundred individuals in the first year.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-07-14T12:51:28.477Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530746/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530746/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530746/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-06-30","Asylum","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answer by Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon on 13 June (HL Deb, col 1004), what new information they have about the fate of the 10,000 unaccompanied refugee children who, according to Interpol, have gone missing; and how many unaccompanied refugee children have arrived in the UK to date.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL908"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530747","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-04","<p>The Government expects to lay Regulations later this year implementing changes to student support arrangements for nurses starting their courses in 2017/18.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Evans of Bowes Park",,"2016-07-04T15:12:50.723Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530747/answer","Biography information for Baroness Evans of Bowes Park","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530747/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530747/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-30","Asylum","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the Department of Health's consultation on changes in how healthcare education for nurses is funded, what are the next steps in the legislative process.","false","Biography information for Lord Harrison",,"Lord Harrison","HL909"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530748","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-12","<p>We are concerned by reports that the nationality of Bahraini Shia cleric Sheikh Isa Qassim is being revoked, and we have raised these concerns at senior levels in the Bahraini government and publicly.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-07-12T14:25:47.707Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530748/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530748/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530748/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-30","Universal Credit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussions they have had with the government of Bahrain following the cancellation of Sheikh Isa Qassim's citizenship.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL910"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530749","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-07-07","<p>The implications of the European referendum result for our membership of the European Atomic Energy Community have yet to be determined. It will be for the Government, under the new Prime Minister, to begin negotiations to exit the EU and determine our future relationship with the European Atomic Energy Community.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-07-07T11:16:27.493Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530749/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530749/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530749/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-06-30","Universal Credit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have any plans to leave the European Atomic Energy Community.","false","Biography information for Lord Inglewood",,"Lord Inglewood","HL911"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530750","Home Office","false","2016-07-14","<p>There are no plans to publish data regarding how many certificates of sponsorship for immigration entry clearance are granted to each licensed sponsoring employer.</p><p>There is no requirement to publish annual information regarding how long sponsor licences are valid for as all sponsor licences are issued for four years, as set out in the published sponsor guidance.</p><p>Sponsorship data by tier and industry type is already published as part of the immigration statistics quarterly releases on the gov.uk website. However there are no plans to specifically publish the top 50 employment categories within which the individual certificates are granted in each year.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-07-14T12:58:08.56Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530750/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530750/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530750/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-06-30","Universal Credit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon on 16 June (HL568), whether they will make available annually information about (1) how many certificates of sponsorship for immigration entry clearance are granted to each licensed sponsoring employer, (2) how long licences are valid, and (3) the top 50 employment categories within which the individual certificates are granted in each year.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL912"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530751","Department of Health","false","2016-07-11","<p>Other European Economic Area (EEA) countries and Switzerland reimburse the United Kingdom for the cost of the National Health Service providing treatment to people they are responsible for under European Union law, including UK nationals insured in another EEA country or Switzerland. In the same way, the Department, on behalf of the UK Government, reimburses other EEA countries and Switzerland for the cost of providing healthcare treatment to people we are responsible for under EU law, irrespective of nationality.</p><p> </p><p>As insurability under EU law is not determined on the basis of nationality, it is not possible to provide information on the number of citizens from each country covered by these rules.</p><p> </p><p>Payment arrangements from the UK to France, Spain and Ireland are as follows:</p><p> </p><p>France:</p><p>- All categories of insured persons: Actual costs (meaning the UK is billed for actual healthcare usage)</p><p>Spain:</p><p>- Temporary Visitors: Actual costs</p><p>- All other categories: Average costs (a lump sum is billed, irrespective of the amount of healthcare received)</p><p>Ireland:</p><p>- Temporary Visitors (not including planned treatment claims or workers): Formula agreement</p><p>- Planned Treatment claims: Actual costs</p><p>- Workers: Waiver agreement between the two countries</p><p>- All other categories: Average costs</p><p> </p><p>The decision on whether to bill on the basis of average costs is for individual EEA countries to make.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL914","2016-07-11T12:42:11.347Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530751/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530751/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530751/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-30","Educational Exchanges","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Prior of Brampton on 13 June (HL566), what the calculation systems are for payments by the UK to France, Ireland and Spain for the cost of providing treatment to people for whom the United Kingdom is responsible under European Union law.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL913"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530752","Department of Health","false","2016-07-11","<p>Other European Economic Area (EEA) countries and Switzerland reimburse the United Kingdom for the cost of the National Health Service providing treatment to people they are responsible for under European Union law, including UK nationals insured in another EEA country or Switzerland. In the same way, the Department, on behalf of the UK Government, reimburses other EEA countries and Switzerland for the cost of providing healthcare treatment to people we are responsible for under EU law, irrespective of nationality.</p><p> </p><p>As insurability under EU law is not determined on the basis of nationality, it is not possible to provide information on the number of citizens from each country covered by these rules.</p><p> </p><p>Payment arrangements from the UK to France, Spain and Ireland are as follows:</p><p> </p><p>France:</p><p>- All categories of insured persons: Actual costs (meaning the UK is billed for actual healthcare usage)</p><p>Spain:</p><p>- Temporary Visitors: Actual costs</p><p>- All other categories: Average costs (a lump sum is billed, irrespective of the amount of healthcare received)</p><p>Ireland:</p><p>- Temporary Visitors (not including planned treatment claims or workers): Formula agreement</p><p>- Planned Treatment claims: Actual costs</p><p>- Workers: Waiver agreement between the two countries</p><p>- All other categories: Average costs</p><p> </p><p>The decision on whether to bill on the basis of average costs is for individual EEA countries to make.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL913","2016-07-11T12:42:11.267Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530752/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530752/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530752/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-30","Apomorphine","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Prior of Brampton on 13 June (HL566), for how many UK citizens currently residing in France, Ireland and Spain they are responsible, and for how many citizens from those countries currently residing in the UK are France, Ireland and Spain responsible respectively.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL914"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530753","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-11","<p>Whilst merchant shipping is vital to the well-being of the country, individual vessels are not considered part of the UK’s critical national infrastructure, as this term tends to refer to fixed physical infrastructure. But transport as a whole is designated as a critical sector for the UK.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Transport regularly liaises with both the ports and shipping industries to address cyber security concerns. A Code of Practice for Ports is scheduled to be published in July 2016. Research into cyber vulnerabilities on vessels has also taken place with the co-operation of shipping companies and it is anticipated that a Code of Practice will be published in due course. In the meantime, we are also working with the International Maritime Organization to address global concerns. Guidelines produced by industry are currently being discussed by the IMO and are available on the Baltic and International Maritime Council website.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-07-11T13:56:03.857Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530753/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530753/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530753/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-06-30","Dairy Farming","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they consider merchant shipping part of the UK's critical national infrastructure; and what advice they give to UK shipping companies about cybersecurity.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL915"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530754","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-07","<p>The implementation of the withdrawal agreement will be a matter for the next government and the new Prime Minister.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2016-07-07T15:46:53.34Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530754/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530754/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530754/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-30","Groceries Code Adjudicator","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the event of the UK's withdrawal from the EU, whether they plan to amend domestic legislation prior to the ratification of any final outcome of negotiations with the EU.","false","Biography information for Viscount Waverley",,"Viscount Waverley","HL916"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530755","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-07","<p>This is a matter for the new Prime Minister and their Cabinet. As the PM has said, we have now got to look at all the detailed arrangements, and Parliament will clearly have a role in making sure that we find the best way forward.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley","HL918","2016-07-07T15:46:38.28Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530755/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530755/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530755/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-30","Groceries Code Adjudicator","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to table motions in both Houses of Parliament to enable Parliament to debate the negotiations for the UK exiting the EU holistically, or whether they intend to table motions to debate individual elements of the negotiations.","false","Biography information for Viscount Waverley",,"Viscount Waverley","HL917"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530756","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-07","<p>This is a matter for the new Prime Minister and their Cabinet. As the PM has said, we have now got to look at all the detailed arrangements, and Parliament will clearly have a role in making sure that we find the best way forward.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley","HL917","2016-07-07T15:46:38.357Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530756/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530756/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/530756/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-30","Agriculture: Subsidies","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether, in the event of the UK's withdrawal from the EU, both Houses would have to approve the final outcome of the negotiations between the UK and the EU.","false","Biography information for Viscount Waverley",,"Viscount Waverley","HL918"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529784","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-07","<p>This will ultimately be up to the new Prime Minister and their team to decide. However, I have been encouraged by the interest coming from a range of non-EU countries, including some of our closest allies.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-07-07T14:01:07.873Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529784/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529784/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529784/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-29","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, when the Government plans to enter into talks with non-EU countries on initiating free trade agreements.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","41458"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529785","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-06","<p>While the UK is still a member of the EU, all rights and obligations will apply. We continue to support the EU’s trade agenda and the UK will participate constructively in EU decision making on trade issues including proceeding with implementation of the agreed EU-Canada Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement (CETA).</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-07-06T09:53:55.4Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529785/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529785/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529785/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529785/answer/previousversion/5788","Biography information for Anna Soubry","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-29","Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the implications of the EU referendum result for his plans to implement the EU-Canada Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement.","false","Biography information for Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","Ochil and South Perthshire","Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","41487"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529786","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-05","<p>While the UK is still a member of the EU, all rights and obligations will apply. We continue to support the EU’s trade agenda and the UK will participate constructively in EU decision making on trade issues. We are taking stock of our position with regard to the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership negotiations.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-07-05T15:25:58.793Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529786/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529786/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529786/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529786/answer/previousversion/5789","Biography information for Anna Soubry","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-29","Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the implications of the EU referendum result for his plans to agree and implement the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership.","false","Biography information for Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","Ochil and South Perthshire","Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","41488"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529788","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-05","<p>While the UK is still a member of the EU, all rights and obligations will apply. We continue to support the EU’s trade agenda and the UK will participate constructively in EU decision making on trade issues.</p><p> </p><p>The Government considers that the Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement (CETA) is a “mixed agreement” consisting of both EU and Member State competence. Provided the European Council agrees, this means that CETA can only take full effect once the UK has decided to ratify it. As part of that ratification process, the complete draft text of the agreement would be laid before Parliament for 21 sitting days. In addition, the Government will ensure the proposals for a Council decision on signature, and subsequently conclusion, will be subject to scrutiny in both houses of the UK Parliament.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-07-05T13:31:44.467Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529788/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529788/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529788/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-29","Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of whether parliamentary approval is required for implementation of the EU-Canada Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement.","false","Biography information for Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","Ochil and South Perthshire","Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","41468"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529789","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-11","<p>There will be no immediate changes to our relationship with the EU. EU law continues to apply to and within the UK, covering both rights and obligations, including those that apply to students, researchers, and businesses.</p><p>The UK economy is fundamentally strong and our research and innovation are world leading. The Government is committed to maintaining and enhancing the strength of our research base, which is why at the Spending Review we committed to protect the science budget in real terms, and protect the funding that flows through Innovate UK in cash terms.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-07-11T15:54:56.647Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529789/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529789/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529789/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-29","Universities: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect of leaving the EU on university research.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","41480"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529790","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-05","<p>A Government consultation seeking views on options to move Land Registry operations to the private sector closed on 26 May. My department is analysing these response to help inform a Government decision. No decision has been taken on the future of Land Registry.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-07-05T10:04:00.38Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529790/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529790/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529790/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-29","Land Registry: Privatisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what criteria his Department plans to use to decide which companies may place bids for the Land Registry.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","41495"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529791","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-04","<p>The new Permanent Secretary Head of the Europe Unit requires a strong track record in advising ministers, working closely with international stakeholders and building collaborative relationships to deliver government objectives. The role also requires high level strategic capabilities and the ability to craft and present a strong vision which others can unite behind. The Cabinet Secretary chose to move Oliver Robbins, an existing Permanent Secretary, into this critical position. Oliver Robbins has the experience and skill to meet all the requiremnts of the job having worked in number of critical departments including HM Treasury, Cabinet Office, in the EU Secretariat, and Home Office. As Principal Private Secretary to two Prime Ministers and as Deputy National Security Adviser, he has extensive experience in advising ministers and working with international partners. As Second Permanent Secretary at the Home Office he has set the overall strategy and policy for immigration, an area which will be of key importance during the negotiations of Britain’s exit from the EU.</p>","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin",,"2016-07-04T16:35:31.393Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529791/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529791/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529791/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-29","Cabinet Office EU Unit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what selection criteria were used to appoint the head of the EU Unit.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","41464"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529792","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-04","<p>The majority of the costs (£137,208) covered Secretariat staff costs. The remaining money was spent on services such as IT, oral evidence sessions, legal fees, and other miscellaneous costs.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-07-04T08:23:17.667Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529792/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529792/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529792/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-29","Independent Commission on Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 16 June 2016 to Question 39672, if he will provide a breakdown of the costs associated with the Independent Commission on Freedom of Information.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","41465"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529793","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-04","<p>The Independent Commission was set up in the usual manner.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-07-04T08:23:58.707Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529793/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529793/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529793/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-29","Independent Commission on Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether a value for money assessment was carried out prior to the setting up of the Independent Commission on Freedom of Information.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","41447"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529794","HM Treasury","false","2016-07-08","<p>The revised UK-Malawi tax treaty was substantially agreed several years ago. A limited number of outstanding issues remain, but once these are resolved we will be seeking to arrange signature.</p><p> </p><p>The UK’s treaty negotiating programme is published on GOV.UK and was last updated on 30 November 2015. It stated that the UK will begin negotiations on double taxation agreements with: Nepal, Romania, Trinidad and Tobago, and Uzbekistan.</p><p> </p><p>It also stated that the UK would work on DTAs and protocols with: Colombia, Fiji, Ghana, Guernsey, India, Isle of Man, Israel, Jersey, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Lesotho, Malawi, Portugal, Russia, Thailand, Turkmenistan, UAE, USA and Uruguay.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","41435","2016-07-08T12:21:49.25Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529794/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529794/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529794/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-29","Taxation: Malawi","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what plans his Department has for the revised UK-Malawi tax treaty to be signed and ratified.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","41434"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529795","HM Treasury","false","2016-07-08","<p>The revised UK-Malawi tax treaty was substantially agreed several years ago. A limited number of outstanding issues remain, but once these are resolved we will be seeking to arrange signature.</p><p> </p><p>The UK’s treaty negotiating programme is published on GOV.UK and was last updated on 30 November 2015. It stated that the UK will begin negotiations on double taxation agreements with: Nepal, Romania, Trinidad and Tobago, and Uzbekistan.</p><p> </p><p>It also stated that the UK would work on DTAs and protocols with: Colombia, Fiji, Ghana, Guernsey, India, Isle of Man, Israel, Jersey, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Lesotho, Malawi, Portugal, Russia, Thailand, Turkmenistan, UAE, USA and Uruguay.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","41434","2016-07-08T12:21:49.313Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529795/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529795/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529795/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-29","Taxation: Treaties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, which tax treaties his Department has under review or plans to review in the near future.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","41435"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529797","HM Treasury","false","2016-07-04","<p>Responses to the Treasury’s recent pensions tax consultation indicated that there was no clear consensus for reform. The Government concluded in its response at Budget 2016 that now is not the right time to undertake fundamental reforms to the pension tax system.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-07-04T13:00:42.023Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529797/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529797/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529797/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-29","Pensions: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 29 June 2016 to Question 41169, whether his Department has made (a) an assessment of the potential merits and (b) an estimate of the potential costs of limiting taxation of pensions to the basic rate.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","41463"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529798","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-07-04","<p>One person without a home is one too many. That is why we have increased central investment to tackle homelessness over the next four years to £139 million. This includes £10 million to support innovative ways to prevent and reduce rough sleeping, building on the success of our No Second Night Out initiative.</p><p>We are also developing a new national £10 million Social Impact Bond fund to help homeless people with the most complex needs move off the streets. It will build on our investment in the world’s first homelessness Social Impact Bond in London.</p><p>As well as this, we will also be launching an additional £100 million programme for low-cost move on accommodation, including for rough sleepers leaving hostels.</p><p>We are determined to ensure that we prevent more people from becoming homeless in the first place so we are working with local authorities, homelessness charities and across departments to consider options, including legislation, to prevent more people from becoming homeless.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-07-04T15:53:44.117Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529798/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529798/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529798/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-06-29","Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department is taking to tackle increases in levels of street homelessness in (a) Bristol and (b) England.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","41466"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529799","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-07-04","<p>As the Secretary of State has stated previously, local papers are the bread and butter of journalism - they part of the communities they serve, and people rely on and respect them. In our manifesto, we committed to consulting on the introduction of a business rates relief for local newspapers in England, which was launched in summer 2015. In the March 2016 Budget, the government announced that local newspapers will be eligible for a business rates discount for two years from April 2017. We are confident that this will help local newspapers maintain a presence on the local high street.</p><p>Our recently published BBC White Paper, 'A BBC for the future: a broadcaster of distinction', sets our our expectation for the BBC to enjoy a positive partnership with the local news sector. The News Media Association (NMA) and the BBC have been working together to develop proposals and good progress has been made in agreeing the principles of a service that will see the BBC providing some funding for local journalists to provide reporting for news providers. These plans will be implemented in consultation with the industry.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-07-04T15:29:45.583Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529799/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529799/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529799/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-06-29","Local Press","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent assessment he has made of the performance of the local newspaper industry; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","41443"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529800","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-07-06","<p>To cover the cost of providing the data about housing stock, we made a one-off grant payment of £5,000 to each local authority with a Housing Revenue Account. No estimate has been made about the ongoing cost of keeping this data up-to-date. The processing and validating of the data is being carried out by departmental officials as part of policy development.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","41441","2016-07-06T16:10:31.287Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529800/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529800/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529800/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-06-29","Council Housing: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the ongoing costs of keeping local authority data on the sale of higher value council homes up-to-date.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","41440"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529801","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-07-06","<p>To cover the cost of providing the data about housing stock, we made a one-off grant payment of £5,000 to each local authority with a Housing Revenue Account. No estimate has been made about the ongoing cost of keeping this data up-to-date. The processing and validating of the data is being carried out by departmental officials as part of policy development.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","41440","2016-07-06T16:10:31.35Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529801/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529801/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529801/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-06-29","Council Housing: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the cost of processing and validating local authority data on the sale of higher value council homes.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","41441"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529803","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-07-04","<p>The Department for Energy and Climate Change will be launching a consultation on how to fulfil the Government's commitment to phase out existing unabated coal as an energy source for power stations shortly. The National Planning Policy Framework and planning practice guidance, sets the planning framework for mineral planning authorities to assess applications for the extraction of coal, they do not address the specific uses of coal.</p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-07-04T16:05:31.687Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529803/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529803/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529803/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-06-29","Coal: Mining","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what account he has taken of the Government's policy to end unabated coal in framing National Planning Policy Framework guidelines on the approval of new coal extraction projects.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","41498"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529804","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-07-06","<p>The total number of voucher codes issued in Na h-Eileanan an Iar constituency under the Basic Broadband Scheme is 13 and this has led to five orders to date.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-07-06T13:31:19.357Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529804/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529804/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529804/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-06-29","Broadband: Na h-eileanan an Iar","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many voucher codes have been issued to date to households in Na h-Eileanan an Iar constituency under the national satellite broadband subsidy scheme; and what proportion of those codes has led to an order.","false","Biography information for Angus Brendan MacNeil","Na h-Eileanan an Iar","Angus Brendan MacNeil","41475"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529808","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-07-06","<p>Following the answer I gave to the hon. Member for York Central (Rachael Maskell) on 6 June 2016 to Question 38675, the Ministry of Defence (MOD) has received approximately 5,200 applications for the Legion d'Honneur between June 2014 and June 2016. We are unable to provide a breakdown by month. As at 24 June the MOD had submitted 3,750 cases to the French authorities. We are not automatically advised when awards are issued, but a list provided by the French authorities on 13 May 2016 showed that 3,200 awards had been made.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>It is not possible to give a meaningful figure for an average waiting time for veterans to receive their awards, as this has reduced steadily, from over a year for initial applications to the current time of around two to three months owing to changes in the processing. Some priority cases, particularly where there are health concerns, are processed much more quickly.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is working closely with the French authorities and we are doing our best to ensure that all awards are issued as soon as possible and at the maximum rate at which they can be produced.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","41348 ; 41371 ; 41404","2016-07-06T15:09:33.49Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529808/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529808/answer","Hansard Extract 6 June 2016 HOC38675.docx","Hansard Extract 6 June 2016 HOC38675.docx","Veterans: Military Decorations","Veterans: Military Decorations","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529808/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-29","Veterans: Military Decorations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 6 June 2016 to Question 38675, how many veterans who have applied for the Legion d'Honneur award are yet to receive that award.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","41450"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529809","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-07-07","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 8 June 2016 to Question 39116 to the hon. Member for Islington South and Finsbury (Emily Thornberry).</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-07-07T14:31:24.843Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529809/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529809/answer","Hansard Extract 8 June 2016 HOC 39116.docx","Hansard Extract 8 June 2016 HOC 39116.docx","Nuclear Disarmament","Nuclear Disarmament","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529809/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-29","Nuclear Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many nuclear warheads the UK currently retains.","false","Biography information for Mr Ronnie Campbell","Blyth Valley","Mr Ronnie Campbell","41453"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529810","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-07-04","<p>Voyager aircraft are not purchased on an individual basis, but are supplied as part of a 27 year Private Finance Initiative (PFI) service, originally signed in March 2008, to provide the Royal Air Force with an air to air refuelling and air transport capability. The total cost of the Voyager PFI service, which includes a fleet of 14 aircraft and associated infrastructure, personnel, maintenance and training costs over this 27 year period is £10.5 billion.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-07-04T15:06:40.197Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529810/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529810/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529810/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-29","Military Aircraft: Ministers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 13 June 2016 to Question 39746, what the original purchase cost was of the Voyager aircraft that has been adapted.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","41446"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529811","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-07-08","<p>I am aware of media reports on Russia's use of incendiary weapons and cluster munitions over the past few weeks, which would constitute a further example of indiscriminate military action in Syria. Incendiary weapons were reported to have been used against civilian areas in Aleppo on 25 June and around the town of Saraqeb in Idlib province on 26 June, causing suffering to the civilian population.</p><p>The UK has always been clear that the use of any weapon without regard for the fundamental legal principles of distinction, proportionality and precaution in attack is illegal and must be condemned. We can see no justification for the way in which these weapons are reported to have been used and call on the Regime and the Russian Government to comply with their obligations under International Humanitarian Law.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-07-08T12:03:33.74Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529811/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529811/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529811/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-29","Syria: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what reports the Government has received on the existence of evidence of the use of banned weapons by Russian forces in Syria; and what representations he has made to the Russian government on that matter.","false","Biography information for Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","Ochil and South Perthshire","Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","41467"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529812","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-07-04","<p>Sir John Parker will report on the national shipbuilding strategy by the Autumn Statement 2016, as stated in the Budget Report 16 March 2016, HC 901, paragraph 2.284.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-07-04T15:07:22.527Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529812/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529812/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529812/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-29","Warships: Shipbuilding","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the current timetable is for the completion and publication of the national shipbuilding strategy headed by Sir John Parker.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","41500"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529814","Department for Education","false","2016-07-06","<p>Funding for local authorities is primarily allocated through the Dedicated Schools Grant, as a single guaranteed (schools block/early year block) unit of funding per pupil. Since the introduction of the dedicated schools grant (DSG) in 2006-07, figures are no longer available to be shown split by phase of education. The following links show the DSG guaranteed unit funding (GUF) and schools block unit funding (SBUF) figures in cash terms for England and Coventry LA from 2011-12 to 2016-17.</p><p>2016-17: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/512095/DSG_2016-17_allocations_spreadsheet_March_2016_final.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/512095/DSG_2016-17_allocations_spreadsheet_March_2016_final.xls</a> (“2016-17 DSG allocations” tab Row 5, 40 Column E)</p><p>2015-16: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/508865/DSG_2015-16_allocations_spreadsheet_v11.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/508865/DSG_2015-16_allocations_spreadsheet_v11.xls</a> (“2015-16 DSG allocations” tab Row 5, 40 Column E)</p><p>2014-15: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/427902/DSG_allocations_spreadsheet_2014_to_2015_May_final.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/427902/DSG_allocations_spreadsheet_2014_to_2015_May_final.xls</a> (“2014-15 DSG allocations” tab Row 6, 41 Column G)</p><p>2013-14: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/292339/DSG_2013-14_allocations__v9.0__FINAL.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/292339/DSG_2013-14_allocations__v9.0__FINAL.xls</a> ((“2013-14 DSG allocations” tab Row 6, 41 Column R)</p><p>2011-12 &amp; 2012-13: <a href="http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20130123124929/http:/www.education.gov.uk/schools/adminandfinance/financialmanagement/schoolsrevenuefunding/settlement2013pupilpremium/a00200465/dedicated-schools-grant-and-pupil-premium-arrangements-for-2012-13" target="_blank">http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20130123124929/http://www.education.gov.uk/schools/adminandfinance/financialmanagement/schoolsrevenuefunding/settlement2013pupilpremium/a00200465/dedicated-schools-grant-and-pupil-premium-arrangements-for-2012-13</a> (“2012-13 DSG GUFs” file, “2012-13 GUFs” tab, Row 6, 42, Column C, D)</p><p>Additionally, since 2011-12 schools have received the Pupil Premium which targets funding at pupils from the most deprived backgrounds to help them achieve their full potential. In 2011-12, the Premium was allocated for each pupil known to be eligible for Free School Meals, looked after children and children of parents in the armed services. In 2012-13 coverage was expanded to include pupils known to have been eligible for Free School Meals at any point in the last six years. The per pupil rates for each type of pupil are shown in following table in cash terms:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Pupil Premium per pupil (£)</p></td><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>2016-17</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Free School Meal Pupil Secondary</p></td><td><p>£488</p></td><td><p>£623</p></td><td><p>£900</p></td><td><p>£935</p></td><td><p>£935</p></td><td><p>£935</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Service Children</p></td><td><p>£200</p></td><td><p>£250</p></td><td><p>£300</p></td><td><p>£300</p></td><td><p>£300</p></td><td><p>£300</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Looked After Children</p></td><td><p>£488</p></td><td><p>£623</p></td><td><p>£900</p></td><td><p>£1900*</p></td><td><p>£1900*</p></td><td><p>£1900*</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>*Also includes children adopted from care.</p><p>More information on Pupil Premium can be found at the following link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/pupil-premium-information-for-schools-and-alternative-provision-settings" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/guidance/pupil-premium-information-for-schools-and-alternative-provision-settings</a></p><p><em><br> </em></p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-07-06T15:41:46.423Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529814/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529814/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529814/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-06-29","Pupils: Per Capita Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the level of funding for secondary schools per pupil was in each of the last six years; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","41483"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529815","Department for Education","false","2016-07-06","<p>Nationally we have protected the core schools budget in real terms to the end of the current Spending Review period, enabling a per-pupil protection for the dedicated schools grant so that the money available for our schools will increase as pupil numbers rise.</p><p>The DSG allocations for Birmingham in 2016-17 are found in the table below:</p><p><strong>Birmingham DSG allocations 2016-17</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2016-17 Schools Block Unit of Funding (SBUF) (£)</p></td><td><p>2016-17 Schools Block (£million)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>5,218.42</p></td><td><p>888.62</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Allocations for future years will be announced in due course.</p><p>We believe that schools should be funded on a consistent and predictable basis, which is why we have proposed to introduce a National Funding Formula. The first stage of our two part consultation closed on 17 April and we are currently considering all the responses. We will be launching the second stage of the consultation, which will include illustrative allocations for all schools and local areas, later in the year.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-07-06T15:39:36.29Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529815/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529815/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529815/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-06-29","Schools: Birmingham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what real-terms funding she has allocated to schools in Birmingham for each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","41496"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529816","Department for Education","false","2016-07-04","<p>Academy trusts are responsible for making their own spending decisions including for consultancy and the salaries they set for staff, although we would expect pay to reflect the size and complexity of the trust. As public bodies trusts must secure value for money. They have transparency obligations which means they must publish annual accounts making clear how much they pay school leaders.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-07-04T15:05:18Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529816/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529816/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529816/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-06-29","Academies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether her Department places any limits on (a) the pay of academy chains' chief executives and (b) payments to consultants.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","41484"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529817","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-07-04","<p>The Energy National Policy Statements (EN1 – Overarching and EN2- Fossil Fuel Electricity Generating Infrastructure) set out the current position with respect to new unabated coal-fired generating stations. We will be launching a consultation on how we will we fulfil the Government’s commitment to phase out existing unabated coal generation shortly.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-07-04T16:25:57.66Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529817/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529817/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529817/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-06-29","Coal: Mining","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what discussions she has had with the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government on ensuring that the Government's policy on unabated coal is reflected adequately in the National Planning Policy Framework guidelines.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","41497"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529819","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-07-05","<p>As my rt. hon. Friend the Prime Minister has said, nothing will change overnight – the UK remains a member of the European Union and existing rules apply.</p><p> </p><p>This is the start of a long and complicated process and the Government will need to consider all factors carefully in implementing the decision of the British people.</p><p> </p><p>We have been clear that we are still committed to making sure consumers have secure, affordable and clean energy now and in the future</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hastings and Rye","Amber Rudd",,"2016-07-05T16:42:24.527Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529819/answer","Biography information for Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529819/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529819/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-06-29","Climate Change","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment her Department has made of the potential effect of leaving the EU on the UK's ability to meet its climate change targets.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","41478"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529820","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-07-06","<p>The UK Management Authority (UKMA), which administers the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES), holds data on imports of hunting trophies into the UK from outside the EU of the most endangered species listed on Annex A of the EU Wildlife Trade Regulations and for six less endangered Annex B species which are subject to stricter controls.</p><p> </p><p>As part of the application process for an import permit, the UKMA must consider whether the import would be harmful to the conservation of the species or on the extent of the territory it occupies. This is called a ‘non-detriment finding’. For animal imports, this determination is made by our scientific advisors, the Joint Nature Conservation Committee, which considers any opinions of the EU’s group of scientific experts in CITES, the Scientific Review Group, and examines available data, taking into account a wide range of factors including the biological status of the species, management programmes in place and trade levels.</p><p> </p><p>Information on how a non-detriment finding is made can be found in CITES Conference Resolution 16.7 (<a href="https://cites.org/eng/res/16/16-07.php" target="_blank">https://cites.org/eng/res/16/16-07.php</a>) and the reference guide to the EU Wildlife Trade Regulations (<a href="http://ec.europa.eu/environment/cites/legis_refguide_en.htm" target="_blank">http://ec.europa.eu/environment/cites/legis_refguide_en.htm</a>).</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-07-06T11:45:52.613Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529820/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529820/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529820/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-06-29","Animal Products: Imports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 28 June 2016 to Question 40996, what statistics the Government collects on the number of hunting trophies from endangered or threatened species which are brought in to the UK; and how the Government defines the sustainable hunting of such species.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","41469"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529821","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-05","<p>We have considered the information presented in the UN report. We note that Non-Governmental Organisations and other bodies, including the UN, do not have access to the same type of information on which to base their conclusions as is available to the Government. In particular we are able to call upon UK and other government sources, including a number of liaison officers in Saudi Headquarters. The UK has supported, and continues to support, the work of the Panels of Experts commissioned by the UN, but we do not always agree with their conclusions.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-07-05T14:11:13.85Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529821/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529821/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529821/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-29","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, with reference to the Answer of 15 February 2016 to Question 24771, what further assessment he has made of the conclusions of the Final Report of the UN Panel of Experts on Yemen.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","41476"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529822","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-08","<p>No UK embassies in Europe are currently closed.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-07-08T13:35:46.84Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529822/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529822/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529822/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-29","Europe: Embassies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether any UK embassies in Europe are temporarily closed.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","41477"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529823","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-11","<p>We are still a member of the European Union and there will be no immediate changes in the circumstances of British citizens elsewhere in the EU. EU institutions have communicated directly to British staff that they continue to have the same rights as other officials of the European Union.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-07-11T14:37:57.157Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529823/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529823/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529823/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-29","EU Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with the EU institutions on the job security of UK citizens employed by those institutions.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","41481"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529824","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-08","As the Prime Minister, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron) has said, there will be no immediate changes in the circumstances of British citizens living in European countries. It will be for the next Prime Minister to determine, along with their Cabinet, exactly the right approach to take in negotiating these provisions going forward but the Government's guiding principle will be ensuring the best possible outcome for the British people.","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-07-08T13:39:51.37Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529824/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529824/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529824/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-29","EU Countries: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the implications of UK withdrawal from the EU for UK pensions and healthcare provision for UK citizens (a) currently residing in other EU member states and (b) wishing to retire to other EU member states.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","41482"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529825","Home Office","false","2016-07-07","<p>The Common Travel Area (CTA) arrangement pre-dates the EU and we remain committed to it. In recent days the Prime Minister and the Taoiseach have reiterated their intention for both countries to work together to maintain the CTA. A meeting between UK and Ireland senior officials has taken place, reinforcing the excellent government and operational level cooperation that already exists.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-07-07T12:31:44.333Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529825/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529825/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529825/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-06-29","Common Travel Area: Republic of Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment her Department has made of the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU on cooperation with Ireland on matters under the Joint Statement Regarding Co-Operation on Measures to Secure the External Common Travel Area Border.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","41433"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529826","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-04","<p>The ongoing conflict is making humanitarian access within Taiz city extremely difficult. The UK is the 4th largest donor to Yemen and we have more than doubled our commitment over the last financial year to £85 million. The UK works with trusted and impartial partners, such as UN agencies and Non-Governmental Organisations who prioritise areas of greatest need such as Taiz, and have good access and a strong track record of delivering and monitoring assistance in difficult places. The UK strongly supports the work of UN Special Envoy, Ismail Ould Cheikh Ahmed, and his efforts to get the Yemeni parties to agree to a political solution which is the best way to bring long-term stability to the whole of Yemen, improve humanitarian access, and address the dire humanitarian situation.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-07-04T15:29:03.793Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529826/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529826/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529826/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-29","Yemen: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what humanitarian assistance the UK is providing to Taiz in Yemen; and whether his Department is engaging in negotiations to end the blockade of that city.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","41485"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529827","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-08","<p>The outcome of the EU referendum does not affect the United Kingdom’s steadfast and longstanding commitment to Gibraltar. We will never enter into arrangements under which the people of Gibraltar would pass under the sovereignty of another State against their wishes. Furthermore, the UK will not enter into a process of sovereignty negotiations with which Gibraltar is not content.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-07-08T13:32:21.543Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529827/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529827/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529827/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-29","Gibraltar: Sovereignty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if the Government will reaffirm its commitment to ensuring Gibraltar remains British sovereign territory as long as it is the will of the inhabitants of Gibraltar.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","41451"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529828","Department of Health","false","2016-07-07","<p>According to the formal Rules of Procedure of the Conference of the Parties, the provisional agenda, together with other conference documents, shall be distributed by the Framework Convention on Tobacco Control (FCTC) Secretariat at least sixty days before the opening day of the session. Once the FCTC Secretariat has published these key papers, the Department will discuss priorities with Ministers. The Department has received parliamentary questions and enquiries from stakeholders on the composition of the delegation to this meeting, which will also be decided when the key papers are published.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","41439","2016-07-07T13:27:29.57Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529828/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529828/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529828/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-29","WHO Framework Convention on Tobacco Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what representations he has received about his Department's participation in the seventh conference of the parties to the WHO framework convention on tobacco control in November 2016.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","41448"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529829","Department of Health","false","2016-07-07","<p>According to the formal Rules of Procedure of the Conference of the Parties, the provisional agenda, together with other conference documents, shall be distributed by the Framework Convention on Tobacco Control (FCTC) Secretariat at least sixty days before the opening day of the session. Once the FCTC Secretariat has published these key papers, the Department will discuss priorities with Ministers. The Department has received parliamentary questions and enquiries from stakeholders on the composition of the delegation to this meeting, which will also be decided when the key papers are published.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","41448","2016-07-07T13:27:29.49Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529829/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529829/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529829/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-29","WHO Framework Convention on Tobacco Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what his Department's priorities are for the 7th Conference of the Parties to the World Health Organisation Framework Convention on Tobacco Control to be held in November 2016.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","41439"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529830","Department of Health","false","2016-07-08","<p>The Prime Minister and numerous Government Ministers including my Rt. hon Friend the Secretary of State have engaged with both European Union (EU) and non-EU counterparts to galvanise action at the global level, through the G7, G20 and United Nations, to raise this issue up to the political agenda. We will continue to work closely with our international partners to implement the World Health Organization Global Action Plan on antimicrobial resistance, focusing on strengthening national action across all sectors.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-07-08T09:56:08.73Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529830/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529830/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529830/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-29","Antimicrobials: Drug Resistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions he has had with his (a) EU and (b) non-EU counterparts on tackling antimicrobial resistance.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","41454"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529831","Department of Health","false","2016-07-08","<p>Discussions between Departmental officials and the Association of the British Pharmaceutical Industry concerning pricing and reimbursement models for antibiotics are ongoing and the topic will in due course feature in the established cross-government dialogue on antimicrobial resistance. Additionally, I am planning United Kingdom-wide collaboration as part of the first meeting of Ministers with portfolio responsibility for life sciences across all devolved administrations of the UK.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-07-08T13:07:46.11Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529831/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529831/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529831/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-29","Antibiotics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions Ministers of his Department have had with their counterparts in the devolved administrations on development of new antibiotics and encouraging innovation in such development through reform of evaluation and reimbursement mechanisms.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","41456"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529832","Department of Health","false","2016-07-04","<p>NHS England publishes each quarter at the following link the number of elective operations cancelled by hospitals for non-clinical reasons on or after the day of admission:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/cancelled-elective-operations/cancelled-ops-data/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/cancelled-elective-operations/cancelled-ops-data/</a></p><p> </p><p>The reasons for the cancellations are not collected.</p><p> </p><p>The National Health Service should do everything it can to reduce cancellations and keep them to an absolute minimum. Where this is unavoidable, patients should receive treatment as soon as possible. This is reinforced by a pledge in the NHS Constitution for all patients who have operations cancelled, on or after the day of admission (including the day of surgery), for non-clinical reasons to be offered another binding date within 28 days, or the patient’s treatment to be funded at the time and hospital of the patient’s choice.</p><p> </p><p>The number of cancelled elective operations as a percentage of admissions has remained at less than 1% in each of the last 10 years.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","41492","2016-07-04T15:50:01.443Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529832/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529832/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529832/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-29","Surgery: Waiting Lists","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to minimise the number of cancelled operations caused by bed shortages.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","41491"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529833","Department of Health","false","2016-07-04","<p>NHS England publishes each quarter at the following link the number of elective operations cancelled by hospitals for non-clinical reasons on or after the day of admission:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/cancelled-elective-operations/cancelled-ops-data/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/cancelled-elective-operations/cancelled-ops-data/</a></p><p> </p><p>The reasons for the cancellations are not collected.</p><p> </p><p>The National Health Service should do everything it can to reduce cancellations and keep them to an absolute minimum. Where this is unavoidable, patients should receive treatment as soon as possible. This is reinforced by a pledge in the NHS Constitution for all patients who have operations cancelled, on or after the day of admission (including the day of surgery), for non-clinical reasons to be offered another binding date within 28 days, or the patient’s treatment to be funded at the time and hospital of the patient’s choice.</p><p> </p><p>The number of cancelled elective operations as a percentage of admissions has remained at less than 1% in each of the last 10 years.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","41491","2016-07-04T15:50:01.553Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529833/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529833/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529833/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-29","Surgery: Waiting Lists","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many cancelled operations were caused by bed shortages in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","41492"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529834","Department of Health","false","2016-07-04","<p>The published Table 2.3 Alcohol Clearances per Adult in the <em>HMRC Alcohol Factsheet </em>provides the most recent alcohol consumption data for the last 25 years.</p><p> </p><p><em>The HMRC Alcohol Factsheet</em> is available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.uktradeinfo.com/Statistics/Statistical%20Factsheets/AlcoholFactsheet1013.xls" target="_blank">https://www.uktradeinfo.com/Statistics/Statistical%20Factsheets/AlcoholFactsheet1013.xls</a></p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-07-04T14:04:29.817Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529834/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529834/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529834/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-29","Alcoholic Drinks: Consumption","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent assessment he has made of trends in the level of alcohol consumption across the last 25 years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","41493"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529836","Department of Health","false","2016-07-06","<p>As of July 2016, 74 services are currently registered – covering all stages of gaining and holding Improving Quality in Physiological Services accreditation.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England does not hold information on the number of services that have been allocated a date and are awaiting an assessment visit by United Kingdom Accreditation Service assessors, or the number of services that failed to gain accreditation after their initial assessment.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England does not hold information on how many paediatric audiology services have reached the level required, using the Self-Assessment and Improvement Tool, to be eligible to apply for Improving Quality in Physiological Services accreditation.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","41472 ; 41474","2016-07-06T09:54:26.443Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529836/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529836/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529836/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-29","Paediatrics: Audiology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many paediatric audiology services have registered for the Improving Quality in Physiological Services accreditation scheme to date.","false","Biography information for Dr Sarah Wollaston","Totnes","Dr Sarah Wollaston","41471"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529837","Department of Health","false","2016-07-06","<p>As of July 2016, 74 services are currently registered – covering all stages of gaining and holding Improving Quality in Physiological Services accreditation.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England does not hold information on the number of services that have been allocated a date and are awaiting an assessment visit by United Kingdom Accreditation Service assessors, or the number of services that failed to gain accreditation after their initial assessment.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England does not hold information on how many paediatric audiology services have reached the level required, using the Self-Assessment and Improvement Tool, to be eligible to apply for Improving Quality in Physiological Services accreditation.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","41471 ; 41474","2016-07-06T09:54:26.507Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529837/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529837/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529837/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-29","Paediatrics: Audiology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many paediatric audiology services have (a) been allocated a date and are awaiting an assessment visit by UKAS inspectors under the Improving Quality in Physiological Services accreditation scheme and (b) failed to gain accreditation after their initial assessment visit, since the accreditation began in 2012.","false","Biography information for Dr Sarah Wollaston","Totnes","Dr Sarah Wollaston","41472"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529838","Department of Health","false","2016-07-07","<p>The measurement of scientific and diagnostic services was more complex than originally envisaged which meant that the 70% target for these services to be part of an accreditation programme was difficult to quantify. NHS England continues to lead a programme of work to increase the number of scientific and diagnostic services that are part of accreditation programmes and demonstrate robust quality assurance measures.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-07-07T14:04:52.04Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529838/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529838/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529838/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-29","Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether NHS England has met the key deliverable in the 2014-15 NHS England business plan to ensure that more than 70 per cent of all scientific and diagnostic services are part of accreditation programmes.","false","Biography information for Dr Sarah Wollaston","Totnes","Dr Sarah Wollaston","41473"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529840","Department of Health","false","2016-07-06","<p>As of July 2016, 74 services are currently registered – covering all stages of gaining and holding Improving Quality in Physiological Services accreditation.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England does not hold information on the number of services that have been allocated a date and are awaiting an assessment visit by United Kingdom Accreditation Service assessors, or the number of services that failed to gain accreditation after their initial assessment.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England does not hold information on how many paediatric audiology services have reached the level required, using the Self-Assessment and Improvement Tool, to be eligible to apply for Improving Quality in Physiological Services accreditation.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","41471 ; 41472","2016-07-06T09:54:26.553Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529840/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529840/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529840/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-29","Paediatrics: Audiology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many paediatric audiology services have reached the level required, using the Self-Assessment and Improvement Tool, to be eligible to apply for accreditation under the Improving Quality in Physiological Services scheme.","false","Biography information for Dr Sarah Wollaston","Totnes","Dr Sarah Wollaston","41474"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529841","Home Office","false","2016-07-05","<p>The Metropolitan Police Service, working with the College of Policing and the Mayor’s Office for Policing and Crime conducted a trial last year.</p><p>The published study ‘Police Camera Evidence: London’s cluster randomised control trials of 'Body Worn Video’ can be found on the College of Policing’s website at: http://www.college.police.uk/News/College-news/Documents/BWV%20report%20Nov%202015.pdf</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-07-05T16:49:23.317Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529841/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529841/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529841/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-06-29","Police: Cameras","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what progress the Metropolitan Police Service has made on piloting and evaluating the use by police officers of body-worn cameras; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","41479"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529842","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-07-04","<p>The number of successful prosecutions under the Dangerous Dogs Act 1991 in each of the last five years can be found in the tables attached. The information was obtained in the document “Outcomes by Offence Tables” as part of the criminal justice system quarterly statistics available on the GOV.UK website.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-07-04T15:13:08.207Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529842/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529842/answer","PQ 41499 - Dangerous Dogs Act 1991 - offences.pdf","PQ 41499 - Dangerous Dogs Act 1991 - offences.pdf","Dangerous Dogs Act 1991 - offences","Dangerous Dogs Act 1991 - offences","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529842/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-06-29","Dangerous Dogs: Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many successful prosecutions there have been under the Dangerous Dogs Act 1991 in each of the last five years; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","41499"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529843","Home Office","false","2016-07-05","<p>Ultimately decisions on the size, composition and deployment of a police force’s workforce are operational matters for individual chief constables, working with their democratically elected Police and Crime Commissioners.</p><p>The proportion of police officers in frontline roles in England and Wales increased from 89% in March 2010 to 92% in March 2015 and from 90% to 93% in Avon and Somerset in the same period. At the same time, the Government has slashed bureaucracy – worth up to 4.5 million hours a year – equivalent to over 2,100 police officers.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-07-05T16:39:39.517Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529843/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529843/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529843/answer","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529843/answer/previousversion/5703","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-06-29","Police: Bureaucracy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the effect of changes in the number of back office staff on the time spent on administrative duties by frontline police officers in (a) Avon and Somerset and (b) England.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","41489"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529844","Home Office","false","2016-07-04","<p>There will be no immediate changes in the circumstances of European nationals who wish to travel, study and work in the UK.</p><p>EU nationals do not currently need to apply for an entry visa, residence card or a permanent residence card in order to enjoy their free movement rights and responsibilities.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-07-04T15:25:12.06Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529844/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529844/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529844/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-06-29","Visas: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what plans her Department has to change visa requirements for EU citizens who wish to travel, study and work in the UK.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","41445"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529845","Home Office","false","2016-07-04","<p>Border Force routinely searches for illicit tobacco at the border, acting as one element of a comprehensive cross-government Tobacco Strategy. Border Force targets and seizes illicit tobacco products, referring seizures on tonHM Revenue &amp; Customs (HMRC) for prosecution.</p><p>In the Budget 2016, it was announced that Border Force would receive an additional £31 million of funding over four years to increase tobacco detection capability by the equivalent of 150 extra officers. HMRC also received additional resources in the summer Budget 2015 to tackle illicit tobacco.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-07-04T13:23:42.707Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529845/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529845/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529845/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-06-29","Tobacco: Smuggling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps she is taking to tackle the illicit trade in tobacco products.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","41449"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529846","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-04","<p>There has been one prosecution under the Female Genital Mutilation Act 2003 since it came into force.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-07-04T11:24:33.43Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529846/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529846/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529846/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-06-29","Female Genital Mutilation: Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prosecutions there have been under legislation on female genital mutilation.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","41490"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529847","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-07-04","<p>Eight offenders were found guilty at all courts of offences related to dog fighting in England and Wales in 2015.</p><p> </p><p>This information was obtained from a manual review of court case files that centrally held data indicated may be relevant, and as such has not been through the same quality assurance processes as for routinely published data.</p><p> </p><p>These figures relate to persons for whom these offences were the principal offences for which they were dealt with. When a defendant has been found guilty of two or more offences it is the offence for which the heaviest penalty is imposed. Where the same disposal is imposed for two or more offences, the offence selected is the offence for which the statutory maximum penalty is the most severe.</p><p> </p><p>The number of offenders found guilty at all courts of offences related to dog fighting in England and Wales in 2014 was disclosed in PQ 9486, linked below, in September 2015 as requested by my hon. Friend the Member for Shipley:</p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-09-08/9486/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-09-08/9486/</a></p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-07-04T14:51:44.09Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529847/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529847/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529847/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-06-29","Dog Fighting: Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many convictions there have been for dog fighting in each of the last two years; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","41494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529848","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-06","<p>The information requested is not held centrally.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-07-06T09:28:33.767Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529848/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529848/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529848/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-06-29","Work Capability Assessment: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many work capability assessment appeals there were in Wales in the last three years.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","41459"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529849","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-06","<p>The information requested is not held centrally.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-07-06T09:27:24.027Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529849/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529849/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529849/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-06-29","Work Capability Assessment: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the average cost to the public purse was of an appeal hearing for a work capability assessment in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","41460"
