a) of his Department's civilian staff based in the UK, (b) military personnel based in the UK, (c) of his Department's civilian staff based in Saudi Arabia and (d) military personnel based in Saudi Arabia were employed by the (i) Saudi Arabian National Guard Communications Project and (ii) Ministry of Defence Saudi Armed Forces Project on 1 April in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","41412"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529248","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-07-04","<p>The UK Lightning Force will be able to conduct all necessary maintenance of the F-35 aircraft at RAF Marham, including electronic equipment, following aircraft arrival in 2018. When components cannot be repaired on the front line and need to be returned to industry, this will be done via a global network of depots. The global repair network will be adopted by all of the F-35 partners and offers significant benefits in terms of economies of scale and operational availability. It does not mean that components specifically have to go back to the US for repair.</p><p>The UK has a through life cost for the F-35, which includes repair costs. I am withholding this information as it has the potential to undermine the UK's commercial position when negotiating contracts with industry.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","41408","2016-07-04T15:08:20.757Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529248/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529248/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529248/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-28","Joint Strike Fighter Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what estimate his Department has made of overall repair costs of an F35 during its operational lifetime.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","41392"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529249","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-07-05","<p>Amnesty International, Human Rights Watch and the United Nations Office of the High Commissioner for Human Rights have alerted us to their online reports on the use of cluster munitions in Yemen, which we are analysing.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2016-07-05T15:06:42.68Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529249/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529249/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529249/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-28","Yemen: Cluster Munitions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what evidence he has received on the possible use of cluster munitions in Yemen by Saudi Arabia.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","41423"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529250","Department for Education","false","2016-07-06","<p>The Government expects all pupils in secondary education to be taught a broad and balanced curriculum, and that includes the opportunity to study a foreign language at Key Stage 3 and 4. In 2010, only 43% of pupils were studying a GCSE in a foreign language, down from 76% in 2000. Since the Government introduced the English Baccalaureate (EBacc), the proportion of the cohort in state schools that are entered for a modern foreign language GCSE increased by 20% between 2011 and 2015. Our ambition is that 90 per cent of pupils in mainstream secondary schools will enter GCSEs in the EBacc subjects, including a foreign language.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-07-06T15:36:07.577Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529250/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529250/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529250/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-06-28","Languages: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent steps her Department has taken to encourage students at Key Stage 3 to take up modern foreign languages.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","41402"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529251","Department for Education","false","2016-07-06","<p>Demand for high-level skills in computing will only grow in the years ahead and will be crucial to supporting a successful economy. It is essential that we have a generation of pupils who have the knowledge and understanding they need to become active creators of digital technology, and not just passive consumers of it. We want them to have a deeper understanding of how digital technologies work and be able to write computer programs.</p><p>Since 2014, computing has been part of the National Curriculum at all four key stages. This replaced the outdated Information and Communications Technology (ICT) programme of study. The computing curriculum focuses on teaching children how computers work, the basics of programming, and encourages them to design computer programs to address real world problems. This includes introducing coding to primary pupils. At primary school, pupils are being taught what algorithms are, how to design and write programs to accomplish specific goals using sequencing, selection and repetition and how to apply logical reasoning to detect and correct errors.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-07-06T15:37:02.667Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529251/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529251/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529251/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-06-28","ICT: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps her Department is taking to ensure that computer coding is taught to children from an early stage in their education.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","41405"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529252","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-07-04","<p>The Department of Energy and Climate Change (DECC) does not produce projections of the cost of energy imports by the UK. The latest available estimate of the cost of UK energy imports is for the year 2015, valued at £37.9 billion.[1] Future costs of energy imports will depend on the volumes traded and also on fuel prices, which are inherently uncertain.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><em><strong>[1]</strong></em><em> The Office for National Statistics publishes estimates of the value of trade according to internationally agreed classifications (SITC), with category 3 comprising most energy products (coal, crude oil, oil products, gas and electricity). This data is republished by DECC in table G7 of the Digest of UK Energy Statistics (DUKES), and shows estimates of the value of energy trade.</em></p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-07-04T16:25:47.127Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529252/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529252/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529252/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-06-28","Energy: Imports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, pursuant to the Answer of 27 June 2016 to Question 40363, what estimate she has made of the cost of energy imports by the UK in each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","41418"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529253","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-07-04","<p>We remain committed to consulting on how we will we fulfil the Government’s commitment to phase out unabated coal and will be launching the consultation shortly.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-07-04T16:20:00.053Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529253/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529253/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529253/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-06-28","Coal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, with reference to her speech of 18 November 2015 on a new direction for UK energy policy, when the terms of reference of the review into coal will be published; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","41414"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529254","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-07-05","<p>For electricity, the Government supports the development of interconnectors to other markets. These allow cross-border trade in electricity, determined by market prices. The GB system currently has 4GW of capacity, and in the Budget the Chancellor set out that it is in British consumers interests that this increases by at least 9GW. This will improve our security of supply, deliver significant benefits to consumers, and help integrate more low carbon generation into the system.</p><p> </p><p>On oil products, DECC policy is to secure a competitive market for suppliers by ensuring smarter regulation and addressing market distortions meaning UK companies - well established in the global oil markets - are freely able to export and import the fuels we need.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-07-05T16:27:32.8Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529254/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529254/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529254/answer","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529254/answer/previousversion/5796","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-06-28","Energy: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assistance her Department provides to UK-based companies seeking to export energy and fuel; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","41415"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529255","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-07-05","<p>A number of stakeholders have suggested the concept of a market stabilising Contracts for Difference (CFD) for Pot 1 technologies. We have not yet decided whether to pursue any of the proposed options at this time.</p><p> </p><p>Our focus has been on delivering the next CFD Allocation Round by the end of 2016 which we announced at the Budget, with £290m for less established technologies. We will be making announcements in due course.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-07-05T16:27:52.987Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529255/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529255/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529255/answer","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529255/answer/previousversion/5797","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-06-28","Electricity Generation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what recent progress has been made on her Department's market stabilisation Contract for Difference policy; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","41416"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529256","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-07-04","<p>The Oil and Gas Authority does not produce a forecast of the proportion of UK energy consumption to be supplied by other countries.</p><p>However, as indicated in the answer to Question 40279, the Oil and Gas Authority publishes projections of UK oil and gas import dependency (defined as net oil and gas imports as a percentage of UK oil and gas demand).[1]</p><p>These projections for 2016-2026 are given in the following table.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Oil and Gas import dependency (%)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>43%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p>44%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2018</p></td><td><p>44%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2019</p></td><td><p>45%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2020</p></td><td><p>46%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>[1] <em>Oil and Gas Authority (February 2016), Production Projections </em><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/503852/OGA_production_projections_-_February_2016.pdf" target="_blank"><em>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/503852/OGA_production_projections_-_February_2016.pdf</em></a></p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-07-04T16:28:21.327Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529256/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529256/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529256/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-06-28","Energy Supply","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, pursuant to the Answer of 27 June 2016 to Question 40279, what forecast the Oil and Gas Authority has made of the proportion of UK energy consumption to be supplied by other countries in each of the next 10 years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","41419"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529257","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-07-04","<p>We are committed to keeping the public forest estate in England in trust for the nation and for it to continue to be sustainably managed. The Forestry Commission has not carried out any public consultation on the ownership of Cannon Hill plantation. The Forest Design Plan approved in 2009, which sets out how the area is to be managed, would have been the subject of a public consultation during the preparation and approval process.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-07-04T10:10:42.49Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529257/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529257/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529257/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-06-28","Forests: Dorset","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what public consultation the Forestry Commission has carried out on the future ownership and use of the Cannon Hill plantation in Ferndown, Dorset.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","41372"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529258","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-07-04","<p>We are committed to keeping the public forest estate in England, including Cannon Hill plantation, in trust for the nation and for it to continue to be sustainably managed by the Forestry Commission.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-07-04T10:14:21.947Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529258/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529258/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529258/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-06-28","Forests: Dorset","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether it is the policy of the Forestry Commission to sell the Cannon Hill plantation in Ferndown, Dorset for development.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","41373"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529259","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-04","<p>I continue to chair the National Flood Resilience Review Group. The review’s report is currently being finalised and is due to be published this summer.</p><p> </p>","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin",,"2016-07-04T07:35:04.977Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529259/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529259/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529259/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-28","National Flood Resilience Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether the Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster continues to chair the National Flood Resilience Review following his appointment to lead the EU Unit.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","41354"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529260","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-07-06","<p>Until we leave the EU, current arrangements for farming, food and drink and our environment remain in place.</p><p> </p><p>Defra will continue to ensure the right policies are in place for a cleaner, healthier environment for everyone. It is also vital that British farming is profitable and remains competitive – it is the bedrock of the food and drink industry, Britain’s largest manufacturing sector.</p><p> </p><p>The priorities for negotiating our exit from the EU will be a matter for the new Prime Minister and their Cabinet.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","41346","2016-07-06T12:44:52.207Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529260/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529260/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529260/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-06-28","Air Pollution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU on regulation relating to air quality.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","41345"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529261","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-07-06","<p>Until we leave the EU, current arrangements for farming, food and drink and our environment remain in place.</p><p> </p><p>Defra will continue to ensure the right policies are in place for a cleaner, healthier environment for everyone. It is also vital that British farming is profitable and remains competitive – it is the bedrock of the food and drink industry, Britain’s largest manufacturing sector.</p><p> </p><p>The priorities for negotiating our exit from the EU will be a matter for the new Prime Minister and their Cabinet.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","41345","2016-07-06T12:44:52.347Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529261/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529261/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529261/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-06-28","Food","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment her Department has made of the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU on the food and drink industry.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","41346"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529262","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-04","<p>The UK supported a UN Human Rights Council resolution in October 2015, which called on the UN to provide technical assistance to the Government of Yemen, assist the Yemeni National Independent Commission of Inquiry, and report back to the next session of the Human Rights Council in September. The UK welcomes Yemen’s commitment to cooperate with the UN on protection of human rights</p><p>We are aware of reports of alleged violations of International Humanitarian Law (IHL) by actors in the conflict and take these very seriously. It is important that all sides conduct thorough and conclusive investigations into all incidents where it is alleged that IHL has been breached. We regularly raise the importance of compliance with International Humanitarian Law with the Saudi Arabian Government and other members of the military Coalition. The Saudis have their own internal procedures for investigations and they announced more detail of how they investigate such incidents of concern on 31 January.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-07-04T14:05:02.033Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529262/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529262/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529262/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-28","Yemen: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will request that the UN Human Rights Council establishes an international commission of inquiry to investigate alleged violations of human rights and international humanitarian law in Yemen by all parties to the conflict in that country.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","41351"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529263","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-06","<p>I refer the Hon. Member to my answer of 14 January in response to Written Question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-01-11/21761/" target="_blank">21761</a> of 11 January from the Hon. Member for Birmingham Hall Green (Mr Godsiff ).</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-07-06T13:54:44.307Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529263/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529263/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529263/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-28","Capital Punishment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if his Department will produce a new Strategy for Abolition of the Death Penalty.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","41363"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529264","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-06","<p>I refer my honourable friend to my answer of 30 June given in response to PQ 41301.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-07-06T15:27:56.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529264/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529264/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529264/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-28","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to hire and train trade negotiators.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","41398"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529265","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-06","<p>We welcome the progress made by the Iraqi Security Forces (ISF) in recapturing Fallujah. Iraqi Prime Minister Haider Al-Abadi declared the city fully liberated on 26 June. Iraqi forces continue to clear pockets of Daesh resistance along with the thousands of Improvised Explosive Devices (IEDs) that have been placed by Daesh in schools, mosques, hospital and homes. The United Kingdom is providing support to the ISF through RAF air strikes, military assistance and training, alongside our coalition partners.</p><p>The UK is also working with the Coalition to support the Government of Iraq in developing plans to stabilise areas, like Fallujah, which have been liberated from Daesh, and by working to provide the governance, services and security necessary to enable the safe return of Iraqis to their homes, including the management of explosive hazards such as IEDs.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-07-06T12:52:12.957Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529265/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529265/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529265/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-28","Iraq: Islamic State","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent reports his Department has received on the progress of Iraqi forces in recapturing Fallujah.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","41394"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529266","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-06","<p>The outcome of the EU referendum does not affect the United Kingdom’s steadfast and longstanding commitment to Gibraltar. We will never enter into arrangements under which the people of Gibraltar would pass under the sovereignty of another State against their wishes. Furthermore, the UK will not enter into a process of sovereignty negotiations with which Gibraltar is not content.</p><p> </p><p>Ensuring a well functioning Gibraltar-Spain border is one of our top priorities. This has not changed. It will take some time for our future relationship with the EU to become clear, but there will be no immediate changes in Gibraltar’s circumstances. There will be no initial changes in the way people can travel or the way services can be sold. Over 12,000 people will still be able to commute across the Gibraltar-Spain border every day, including a significant number of Spanish workers. As we move forward in negotiating the United Kingdom’s withdrawal from the EU, we will work in partnership with the Government of Gibraltar to ensure Gibraltar’s interests are protected and advanced.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-07-06T14:00:38.033Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529266/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529266/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529266/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-28","Gibraltar: Spain","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps his Department is taking in response to the outcome of the EU referendum to maintain the existing border between Gibraltar and Spain.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","41409"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529267","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-06","<p>The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond), met Secretary of State John Kerry in London on 27 June. Both Governments agree that an unbreakable bond exists between the US and the UK; that Britain's global role remains undiminished, and that the Special Relationship remains a strong and crucial relationship.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-07-06T15:38:05.987Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529267/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529267/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529267/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-28","USA: Foreign Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, when he plans to meet his US counterparts to discuss the effect of the recent EU referendum on UK-US relations.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","41393"
